"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417640","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government's policy on the future status of Somaliland is that it is for Somalia and Somaliland to determine their future relationship, and for neighbouring countries in the region to take the lead in recognising any new arrangements or change in status.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-14T10:10:02.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417640/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417640/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Somaliland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on the future status of Somaliland.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","9564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417641","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) regularly meets with a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe. Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly and can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-16T16:35:21.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417641/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417641/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which external organisations he has met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many times he has met each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417642","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","Our current method of recording deaths in custody does not separate those who died in police custody from the overall figure of those who died in custody. Prior to May 2012 we have no statistics on death in custody of British nationals overseas. From May to December 2012 we are aware of two British nationals who died in custody overseas. In 2013 we are aware of ten cases and in 2014 of eleven. This year, up until 31 August, we have been made aware of four cases. To break down the location of death in custody for figures prior to May 2012 would require detailed searches of all detainee records, which would be of disproportionate cost.","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-16T12:13:26.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417642/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417642/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","British Nationals Abroad: Police Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many British nationals have died in police custody in other countries in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417643","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","The FCO works very closely with DEFRA to combat the Illegal Wildlife Trade (IWT) and eradicate the poaching of elephants, rhinos, and other animals, reflecting HMGâs global leadership on this issue. Our Posts across Africa, are very active on this. Our Ambassadors and High Commissioners regularly raise the issue of IWT at the highest level, and FCO Ministers raise IWT with their counterparts wherever possible, including at multilateral fora. I recently wrote to the Zimbabwean Minister for Environment, Water, and Climate to advance our working together on this issue. The FCO secured attendance of Ministers from Kenya, Uganda, Namibia and 15 other African countries at the London Conference on IWT in February 2014. We also gained the participation of Ministers from these countries, plus South Africa and 12 other African countries, to attend the UK supported follow-up conference in Kasane, northern Botswana, on 25 March 2015 for further discussions. These initiatives have resulted in collective conference declarations with 40 ambitious commitments, to eradicate IWT through demand reduction, strengthening law enforcement and legal deterrents, and protecting sustainable livelihoods.","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-16T15:00:11.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417643/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417643/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Africa: Wildlife","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with his counterparts in (a) Kenya, (b) Uganda, (c) South Africa, (d) Namibia and (e) other countries in Africa on measures to stop the killing of elephants and rhinos.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417644","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-11","We share the concerns of the US State Department Report on Human Rights practices in Afghanistan which is why Afghanistan is one of 27 human rights priority countries for the UK. We recognise that although there has been significant progress in Afghanistan on human rights, particularly womenâs rights since 2001, significant challenges remain and gains remain fragile. We have made long-term commitments to the country's future through financial aid and political support. In return, we expect to see clear progress from the Afghan National Unity Government, including on corruption, good governance and human rights. The UK Government is working closely with the Government of Afghanistan, local and international Non-Governmental Organisationss, civil society organisations and international partners to improve human rights, specifically the status of women and girls in Afghanistan, to enable them to participate fully in Afghanistanâs future.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-11T13:17:27.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417644/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417644/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Afghanistan: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the implications for its policies of the US State Department report on Human Rights Practices in Afghanistan for 2014, published in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","9416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417645","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>At a meeting of the informal Justice and Home Affairs (JHA) Council on 9 July Member States agreed to resettle over 22,500 people, taking account of priority regions for resettlement including North Africa, the Middle East and the Horn of Africa, focusing in particular on the countries where Regional Development and Protection Programmes are implemented. The UK made it clear that it would not be participating in an EU resettlement scheme as we already operate successful national schemes. At the extraordinary JHA Council on 14 September, the Home Secretary made clear the Government's view that resettlement from the region is an essential part of the response to the situation in Syria. All UK resettlement activity will continue to be delivered under existing national programmes, including the expanded Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme under which we expect to resettle up to 20,000 Syrians in need of protection during this Parliament.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-16T16:21:37.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417645/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417645/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Refugees: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received from the President of the European Commission on the proposed expansion of the European Resettlement Scheme for refugees.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","9355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417646","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>Turkey is a NATO ally and a valued partner for the UK. Foreign and Commonwealth Office Ministers and officials have regular discussions with Turkish counterparts covering a wide range of issues. On 14 August 2015, I met Volkan BozkÄ±r, the then Turkish Minister for EU Affairs and Chief Negotiator. We discussed the political and security situation in Turkey and the region.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td></tr></tbody></table>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-16T16:24:27.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417646/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417646/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Turkey: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Turkish counterpart on the political unrest in that country.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","9372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417647","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Foreign Secretary has regular discussions with his French counterpart on a range of issues.</p><p>Alongside the more than sixty members of the Global Coalition to Counter ISIL, the UK and France are working closely together to defeat and degrade ISIL and counter violent extremism more widely. This includes undertaking airstrikes against ISIL targets in Iraq.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-15T14:33:57.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417647/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417647/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Iraq: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his French counterpart on air strikes in Iraq.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","9373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417648","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>We are aware of reports that Russia may have deployed military personnel and aircraft to Syria, and we are monitoring those reports closely. <br><br>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs discussed Syria with Foreign Minister Lavrov in June and discussions continue at official level.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-16T16:27:49.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417648/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417648/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Syria: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Russian counterpart on that country's escalating military intervention in Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","9374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417649","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The scheme will continue to prioritise the most vulnerable: people requiring urgent medical treatment, survivors of torture and violence, and women and children at risk. We are discussing with the UNCHR and other partners the extent to which the current criteria should be extended to ensure that a greater number of people qualify for the scheme.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:51:27.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417649/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417649/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish the expanded criteria for the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","9412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417650","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Gateway programme demonstrates the UKâs proud tradition of providing protection to refugees; and of the UKâs commitment to supporting UNHCRâs global effort to provide durable solutions to the plight of refugees. Since the first arrivals in March 2004, the UK has resettled over 6,300 refugees under the Gateway programme. The current commitment is to resettle 750 refugees per year, generally those in protracted situations, and has been fully met over the last two years. The Mandate Refugee Scheme is designed to resettle individual refugees from anywhere in the world who have been recognised as refugees by UNHCR, and judged by them to be in need of resettlement; and who have a close family member in the UK who is willing to accommodate them.</p><p>Therefore this scheme has no quota. There are no plans to expand either of these schemes over the term of this Parliament and we will continue with our commitment to offer protection to those in most need, along side those beneficiaries of the Vulnerable Personâs Relocation scheme.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-17T11:23:28.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417650/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417650/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Asylum: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Statement on Syrian Refugees and Counter-terrorism of 7 September 2015, Official Report, column 24, how many additional refugees the Government plans to take under the (a) Gateway programme and (b) Mandate programme over the duration of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","9466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417651","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK has been involved in many discussions with other Member states. That includes participation in EU Council of Ministers meetings, as well as bilateral discussions with other Member States. The Home Secretary will continue to discuss these matters with EU partners including at forthcoming Justice and Home Affairs Council meetings.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:50:48.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417651/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417651/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Refugees: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received from Heads of Government in other EU countries on the proposed European Resettlement Scheme for refugees.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","9354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417652","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>No such discussions have taken place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Commissioners are legally required to provide funding for treatments and drugs recommended in National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) technology appraisal guidance within three months of NICEâs final guidance.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T14:54:33.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417652/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417652/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with NHS England on recent guidance stating that NICE-recommended medicines will be funded from day 90 of publication.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","9350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417653","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The attached table provides â for each trust where there is data showing that either primary breast reconstruction, secondary breast reconstruction, or both, were carried out â the hospitals within that trust that have a multi-disciplinary team treating breast cancer. There are 191 hospitals in the list, which is an approximate number and may vary.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","9365","2015-09-16T15:36:07.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417653/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417653/answer","Hospital sites providing breast reconstruction- breast cancer treatment.xlsx","Sites providing breast reconstruction/ treatment ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417653/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which hospitals offer breast reconstruction to breast cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","9366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417654","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>NHS England is in the process of concluding a review of these two policies and is aiming to finalise the way forward, including a position on public consultation, by the end of September.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:03:56.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417654/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417654/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent progress NHS England has made on developing new policies for in-year service developments and individual funding requests; and if NHS England will commit to a public consultation on these matters.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","9346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417655","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>NHS England has committed to consult further with the public if ranking methodology is planned to be used in its decisions over the investment in specialised service developments. NHS England is considering options to support these difficult decisions.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:14:42.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417655/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417655/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Health Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent progress NHS England has made in developing a scorecard to consider the relative ranking of specialised services in (a) clinical and (b) cost effectiveness; and if NHS England will commit to a public consultation on ranking specialised services.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","9347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417656","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>In June 2015, NHS England published its response to its consultation, <em>Investing in Specialised Services</em>. This is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2015/06/nhse-respns-publictn-17-06-15.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2015/06/nhse-respns-publictn-17-06-15.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In it, NHS England stated that it had agreed with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) that both organisations should jointly explore the extent to which NICE may play a role in delivering clinical evidence reviews as part of the process for assessing proposed new investments in future years. This was in response to submissions received during the consultation, calling for the process of reviewing the clinical evidence for proposed new investments in specialised services to be led by NICE.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that no decisions in this regard have yet been made. Preliminary discussions across the two organisations are expected to commence this month.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T14:56:00.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417656/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417656/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS England has had discussions with NICE on the assessment of medicines in specialised commissioning.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","9348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417657","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>Over the last 15 years, services for pancreatic cancer have been significantly strengthened within the National Health Service. This includes clearer diagnostic pathways, decision making by specialist multi-disciplinary teams and centralisation of pancreas surgery within specialist teams.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Between 1999 and 2009, following reorganisation of pancreas services, there are now twice as many patients accessing surgery, and one year survival has increased by 5%. The benefits of the United Kingdom model are recognised internationally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is recognised that pancreatic cancer is a challenging disease for a number of reasons. There is a lack of any effective drug therapies and research opportunities are restricted by the small number of patients with the disease (approximately 7,000 annually), and the relatively low survival rates.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Symptoms are variable and difficult to identify, and there is presently no diagnostic test, although a test is in the research phase.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-11T12:25:49.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417657/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417657/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Pancreatic Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the level of provision of pancreatic cancer treatment on the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417658","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellenceâs (NICE) guidance is based on a thorough assessment of the available evidence and is developed through wide consultation with stakeholders. NICE makes every effort to ensure that appropriate stakeholders, including clinical experts, are able to engage with the development of its guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of NICEâs technology appraisal process, clinical specialists, commissioning experts and patient experts are invited by the Appraisal Committee to provide written evidence and attend the Committee meeting to help in the Committee's discussion of the technology being appraised.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England is responsible for administering the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF) and decisions on which treatments are included on the national CDF list are made by the CDF clinical panel. The panel includes expert oncologists, oncology pharmacists and patient representatives.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T11:55:39.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417658/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417658/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Pancreatic Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that expert clinicians are consulted when assessing new treatments for pancreatic cancer.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417659","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Personal Social Services Research Unit at the University of Kent estimates that the average cost of training a nurse in 2013 was Â£78,604. This figure reflects the total cost of training and therefore includes costs funded through the public purse, including the NHS bursary, and by the student.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>National Health Service organisations are best placed to decide how many staff they employ and how best to recruit those staff to meet services tailored to the needs of their patients and local communities, to deliver safe care.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-11T12:07:22.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417659/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417659/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of training a UK citizen as a nurse; and what assessment he has made of how this figure compares with the costs of recruiting nurses from overseas.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","9401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417660","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Independent Cancer Taskforceâs new strategy, <em>Achieving World-Class Cancer Outcomes: A Strategy for England 2015-2020</em>, which recommends improvements across the cancer pathway, was published on 19 July 2015. It will reduce incidence of cancer and improve services and outcomes for cancer patients, in particular survival rates. We will work with the National Health Service, charities and patient groups to deliver it.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our cancer survival rates are at an all-time high and continue to improve, but we know we need to do more to be among the best in the world, and that is what we aim to achieve.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-11T13:13:15.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417660/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417660/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Cancer: Mortality Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of changes in cancer survival rates in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","9393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417661","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Investigations currently being conducted by Monitor, under the powers given to it by the Health and Social Care Act 2012, will continue when Monitor joins with the Trust Development Authority to form NHS Improvement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-16T15:30:28.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417661/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417661/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Monitor","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the current investigations being carried out by Monitor will continue following its move to single leadership with the Trust Development Authority; and whether those investigations will fall to be supervised by the new single leadership.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","9415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417662","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The attached table provides â for each trust where there is data showing that either primary breast reconstruction, secondary breast reconstruction, or both, were carried out â the hospitals within that trust that have a multi-disciplinary team treating breast cancer. There are 191 hospitals in the list, which is an approximate number and may vary.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","9366","2015-09-16T15:36:07.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417662/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417662/answer","Hospital sites providing breast reconstruction- breast cancer treatment.xlsx","Sites providing breast reconstruction/ treatment ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417662/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospitals offer breast reconstruction to breast cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","9365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417663","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The latest rise in drug misuse deaths â particularly in the North East â is a great concern and highlights the need for further local and national action. We need to ensure the most vulnerable users can access drug treatment and harm reduction services, where they have the best chance of recovery.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England will continue to support local authorities in delivering effective recovery services for everyone who needs them. They are providing local authorities and commissioners with expert advice, evidence, and management information including outcomes and value for money data. This can help to ensure that the local services are evidence-based, effective and integrated with local health, housing and employment support.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-11T13:27:25.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417663/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417663/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce the mortality rate from drug misuse in the North East.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","9389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417664","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Cancer Drugs Fund panel considered a number of drug/indications for reprioritisation in July 2015. The panelâs decisions were announced on 4 September 2015 and are available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/pe/cdf/cdf-drug-sum/" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/pe/cdf/cdf-drug-sum/</a></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T11:57:19.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417664/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417664/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Pancreatic Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the reasons are for the most recent NHS England review of the pancreatic cancer drug available on the national Cancer Drugs Fund.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417665","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The national Cancer Drugs Fund Panel followed NHS Englandâs Standard Operating Procedures for the Cancer Drugs Fund during the process of decision making. The Panel includes members from patient groups. In accordance with the Standard Operating Procedures, delegated members of the panel met with patient groups this week to explain the panelâs decisions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T11:59:14.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417665/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417665/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with which patient groups did NHS England consult before the decision was taken to remove 25 treatments from the Cancer Drugs Fund.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417666","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>NHS England is working with manufacturers seeking to maintain drug and indication combinations within the Cancer Drugs Fund.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T12:04:15.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417666/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417666/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of patients who will be denied access to treatments no longer available on the national Cancer Drugs Fund list from 4 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417667","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Clinical Priorities Advisory Group continues to meet every month and advises NHS England on proposals that are being considered as an âIn Year Service Developmentâ for the 2015/16 financial year. There will be a meeting to consider service development proposals for the 2016/17 financial year. The date of that meeting has not yet been set.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:00:43.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417667/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417667/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Clinical Priorities Advisory Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 15 June 2015 to Question 1281, when NHS England's Clinical Priorities Advisory Group will next hold a meeting on prioritisation.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","9468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417668","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-11T12:12:49.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417668/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417668/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","General Practitioners: Maternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of GP maternity cover posts have been left unfilled in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","9490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417669","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Review will make recommendations to Government on reforms to accelerate access for National Health Service patients to innovative medicines and medical technologies (including devices, diagnostics and digital), making our country the best place in the world to design, develop and deploy these products. This includes looking at regulation, reimbursement, assessment and uptake.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T14:57:13.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417669/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417669/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the Innovative Medicines and MedTech Review plans to investigate how to reduce the period between NICE approval of a medicine and its funding by NHS trusts.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","9467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417670","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>NHS England has advised that its standard time frame for a treatment recommended in a National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) technology appraisal to be commissioned will be 90 days except in exceptional circumstances. These include where:</p><p> </p><p>- the approved technology provides significant benefit to the patient population who will receive the technology compared to the current standard of care;</p><p> </p><p>- there is significant unmet need in the target population such that patients may come to significant harm if the technology is not commissioned earlier; and</p><p> </p><p>- the approved technology will release healthcare resources such that funding can be redirected to support other commissioning priorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Decisions to fund any recommended technology prior to 90 days will be made by NHS Englandâs Specialised Commissioning Oversight Group.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T14:58:28.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417670/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417670/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, under what criteria NHS England choose to fund a NICE-approved medicine before the three month period following the publication  of a positive NICE recommendation; and what steps NHS England is taking to encourage uptake of medicines after positive NICE recommendations as soon as possible.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","9566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417671","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) services are the commissioning responsibility of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and are often provided linked to maternity services. FGM services are not commissioned by NHS England at a national level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The commissioning of such services by CCGs is being developed, and can now be informed by the publication of national statistics by the Health and Social Care Information Centre. For the first time these show how many patients are treated who have FGM, with data published about local areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department recently published FGM guidance for commissioners setting out the elements of a successful and safe service. The aim of the document is to highlight what commissioners might want to consider when developing a new FGM service and it can be used by any healthcare commissioners, clinical commissioning groups, area teams and service development leads.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are details of 14 FGM clinics across England published on the NHS Choices website at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/AboutNHSservices/sexual-health-services/Pages/fgm-health-services-for-women.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/AboutNHSservices/sexual-health-services/Pages/fgm-health-services-for-women.aspx</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-16T12:09:54.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417671/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417671/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what services NHS England commissions to support women and girls who have suffered female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","9562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417672","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the European Union (EU) and campaigning to keep the United Kingdom in the EU on that basis. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Governmentâs priorities in Europe.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-16T12:14:33.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417672/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417672/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Department of Health: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many officials in his Department are engaged in research into the effects of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417673","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the European Union (EU) and campaigning to keep the United Kingdom in the EU on that basis. Officials regularly meet with a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe. Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","9521","2015-09-16T12:16:22.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417673/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417673/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Department of Health: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which external organisations he has met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many times he has met each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417674","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the European Union (EU) and campaigning to keep the United Kingdom in the EU on that basis. Officials regularly meet with a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe. Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","9539","2015-09-16T12:16:22.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417674/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417674/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Department of Health: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which external organisations officials in his Department have met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many meetings such officials have had with each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417675","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>No assessment has been made of the ease of access to treatment and services for Tuberous Sclerosis Complex (TSC); any such assessment would need to carefully consider the wide-range of need associated with TSC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Everolimus is a licensed oral treatment for TSC and has been licensed by the European Medicines Agency. NHS Englandâs process for introducing new treatments for use in the services that it commissions involves the production of a clinical commissioning policy; this process is currently underway for Everolimus in the treatment of TSC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","9631","2015-09-16T15:02:52.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417675/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417675/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Tuberous Sclerosis: Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the ease of access to Everolimus for Tuberous Sclerosis Complex sufferers.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","9630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417676","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>No assessment has been made of the ease of access to treatment and services for Tuberous Sclerosis Complex (TSC); any such assessment would need to carefully consider the wide-range of need associated with TSC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Everolimus is a licensed oral treatment for TSC and has been licensed by the European Medicines Agency. NHS Englandâs process for introducing new treatments for use in the services that it commissions involves the production of a clinical commissioning policy; this process is currently underway for Everolimus in the treatment of TSC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","9630","2015-09-16T15:02:52.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417676/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417676/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Tuberous Sclerosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the ease of access to treatment and services for Tuberous Sclerosis Complex; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","9631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417677","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>National Health Service organisations are best placed to decide how many staff they employ and how best to recruit those staff to meet services tailored to the needs of their patients and local communities, to deliver safe care.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-11T12:24:18.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417677/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417677/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Nurses: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the budget made available for nurse recruitment by NHS trusts in England and Wales in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417678","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>I met with the parents of children with Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy and Muscular Dystrophy UK, alongside the hon. Member for Winchester (Steve Brine) on 8 September 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I also met with the Muscular Dystrophy Campaign (MDC) alongside the hon. Member for Leeds North West (Greg Mulholland) on 26 March 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The former Minister of State for Care Services (Norman Lamb) met with the hon. Member for Blaydon (David Anderson) and a representative of the MDC group on 2 March 2015 where the issue of funding for Translarna was raised.</p><p> </p><p><br> <br></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T12:01:26.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417678/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417678/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Muscular Dystrophy: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received from charities and patient groups on access to the drug Translarna for the treatment of Duchenne muscular dystrophy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417679","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>A copy of the terms of reference of the independent maternity review is attached.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-11T12:15:32.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417679/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417679/answer","maternity-rev-tor.pdf","Maternity Review Terms of Reference","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417679/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Maternity Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will place in the Library NHS England's terms of reference for the independent maternity review.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417680","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>NHS England colleagues advise that the scope of the independent maternity review is from conception to the end of the postnatal period (six weeks after birth). Postpartum contraception is within scope insofar as it forms part of good postnatal care.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-11T12:16:50.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417680/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417680/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Contraceptives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether postpartum contraception is being considered as part of NHS England's independent maternity review; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417681","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>Mental health problems are not uncommon during pregnancy, with around 12% of women experiencing depression and 13% experiencing anxiety at some point. Research has also found that around one in five new mothers experience harassment or negative comments from colleagues, employers or managers when pregnant or returning to work following maternity leave.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Pregnancy and disabilities are both protected characteristics which means that pregnant and disabled employees have protection against unfair treatment, discrimination or dismissal at work. Mental ill health is considered a disability under the Disability Discrimination Act if it has a âsubstantialâ and âlong-termâ negative effect on a personâs ability to do normal daily activities. Addressing all issues concerning perinatal mental health is a key priority of the Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Health care professionals involved in maternity care should follow National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance for the recognition, assessment, care and treatment of mental health problems in women during pregnancy and the postnatal period (up to one year after childbirth) and in women who are planning a pregnancy. Women who know they are pregnant should contact their local maternity service for a full assessment of their health, risk factors and choices so that a personalised plan of care can be prepared. Midwives are also trained to identify women who may require additional support, including for mental health issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This Government has committed to providing an additional Â£75 million over the next five years for services to support women with mental ill health in the perinatal period.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-11T12:14:08.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417681/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417681/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Pregnancy: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effects on maternal mental health of pregnancy and maternity discrimination at work; and what steps he plans to take to address this issue.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","9594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417682","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government is committed to improving the lives of those affected by rare diseases and the United Kingdom is a recognised leader in the research, treatment and care for rare diseases.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Through its technology appraisal programme, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) develops authoritative, evidence-based guidance for the National Health Service on whether drugs and treatments referred to it by Ministers represent a clinically and cost effective use of NHS resources. NHS commissioners are legally required to fund drugs and treatments recommended by NICE within three months of the publication of final guidance. Wherever possible, NICE aims to issue technology appraisal guidance on the use of a drug close to the time of licensing. Where NICE guidance is not available, it is for NHS commissioners to take funding decisions based on an assessment of the available evidence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Accelerated Access Review will make recommendations to the Government on reforms to accelerate access for NHS patients, including those with rare diseases, to ensure they can access effective and innovative treatments as early as possible in a way that represents value to the NHS.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T13:40:05.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417682/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417682/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will take steps to reduce the time taken to approve for use drugs for the treatment of rare conditions and diseases; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417683","Department of Health","false","2015-09-15","<p>This is an ongoing legal case and we do not propose to report monthly on the costs of the case. These will be accounted for at the end of the process.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-15T15:59:36.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417683/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417683/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Department of Health: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 15 July 2015 to Question 6508, for what reasons his Department cannot report monthly on the litigation and Counsel's costs relating to the Freedom of Information request for the former Secretary of State for Health's diary of engagements referred to in Information Commissioner Decision Note No. FS50406024 and the subsequent appeals.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","9617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417684","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Public Health England guidance provides examples of potential recipients for supply of naloxone locally but does not restrict the scope of the new regulations. The new regulations will widen access to naloxone so that any person employed or engaged in the provision of drug treatment services can supply naloxone to others in the course of their lawful drugs work, for the purposes of naloxone being available to save life in emergency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The regulations define drug treatment services as those provided by, on behalf of, or under arrangements made by, one of the following bodies: (a) an NHS body; (b) a local authority; (c) Public Health England; or (d) Public Health Agency.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-11T12:22:10.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417684/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417684/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Naloxone","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether availability of the drug Naloxone, under the new regulations to be introduced on 1 October 2015, will be restricted to those categorised in current Public Health England guidance.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","9597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417685","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>Health Education England is responsible for delivering a better health and healthcare workforce for England and for ensuring a secure future supply of nurses with the right skills, values and behaviours to meet future demand.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The number of nurses in Wales is a devolved issue. Information on the number of nurses employed in Wales may be available online at the following address:</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>http://gov.wales/topics/health/?lang=en</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-11T12:03:17.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417685/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417685/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number of nurses that will be employed by NHS trusts in England and Wales in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417686","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Early Access to Medicines Scheme (EAMS) was launched in April 2014. Its purpose is to support access in the United Kingdom to unlicensed or off-label medicines representing a significant advance in treatment in areas of unmet medical need.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>EAMS is a 2 step process. First, the Promising Innovative Medicine designation by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) is designed to give an early signal that based on early clinical evidence the medicine may be a possible candidate for EAMS and thus have the potential to be of value in areas of unmet medical need. There have been eight EAMS Promising Innovative Medicines designations issued so far.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Second, the EAMS scientific opinion by the MHRA, which we envisage will usually be towards the end of the development process, enables prescribers and patients to decide if the EAMS medicine might be suitable for that individual patient. Four positive EAMS scientific opinions have been issued.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For medicines granted a scientific opinion and which then receive a marketing authorisation, it is for commissioners to make funding decisions in advance of any technology appraisal guidance from the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There will be a review of EAMS as part of the Accelerated Access Review currently underway.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T12:28:34.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417686/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417686/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of patient access to innovative drugs approved under the MHRA's Early Access to Medicines Scheme ahead of NICE assessments and in the absence of any planned Cancer Drugs Fund meetings.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","9598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417687","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is currently consulting on reform of police funding arrangements in England and Wales. The consultation seeks views on the principles of the Governmentâs proposed model.</p><p>Final allocations for police force areas have not been set and will not be determined until we have consulted on the principles.</p><p>We will publish a Government response setting out force level impacts in due course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","9586 ; 9622","2015-09-14T15:35:01.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417687/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417687/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Greater Manchester Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect on funding for Greater Manchester Police of the replacement of the Police Allocation Formula.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","9585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417688","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is currently consulting on reform of police funding arrangements in England and Wales. The consultation seeks views on the principles of the Governmentâs proposed model.</p><p>Final allocations for police force areas have not been set and will not be determined until we have consulted on the principles.</p><p>We will publish a Government response setting out force level impacts in due course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","9585 ; 9622","2015-09-14T15:35:01.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417688/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417688/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of which Police Force in England and Wales will experience the highest percentage change in its funding as a result of the proposed replacement of the Police Allocation Formula.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","9586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417689","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is currently consulting on reform of police funding arrangements in England and Wales. The consultation seeks views on the principles of the Governmentâs proposed model.</p><p>Final allocations for police force areas have not been set and will not be determined until we have consulted on the principles.</p><p>We will publish a Government response setting out force level impacts in due course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","9585 ; 9586","2015-09-14T15:35:02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417689/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417689/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Greater Manchester Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the statement of 21 July 2015 on Police Funding: England and Wales, HCWS 164, what the effect on Greater Manchester Police will be of following the replacement of the Police Allocation Formula.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","9622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417690","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The colleges in question were suspended due to their sponsorship of students with questionable or invalid English language test certificates; and a poor level of compliance their with sponsorship duties. All of the colleges were given the opportunity to submit detailed representations against the suspension. Those that failed to address adequately the reasons for suspension subsequently had their sponsor licence revoked.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:56:45.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417690/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417690/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Educational Institutions: Bradford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2015 to Question 6880, what the circumstances and reasons were for the suspension of the licence of Bradford College of Management; and what the circumstances and reasons were for the suspension and revocation of the licences of (a) Bradford Metropolitan College and (b) Bradford Regional College.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417691","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. Officials regularly meet with a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:51:39.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417691/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417691/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Home Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which external organisations officials in her Department have met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many meetings such officials have had with each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417692","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. Home Office Ministers regularly meet a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe. Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:57:07.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417692/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417692/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Home Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which external organisations she has met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many times she has met each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417693","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Governmentâs priorities in Europe.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:53:05.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417693/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417693/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Home Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many officials in her Department are engaged in research into the effects of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417694","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>As previously stated, Her Majestyâs Government takes its commitments to its international obligations very seriously and asylum cases require special care. These obligations cannot permit the disclosure of information that could in turn make these individuals identifiable. This remains the position, and extends to the applications for other forms of leave. In view of the small number of individuals involved, disclosure of nationalities may lead to identification.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:56:28.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417694/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417694/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Immigration: Commonwealth Games 2014","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 15 July 2015 to Question 5239, from what countries of origin people were (a) who applied for or (b) were granted (i) asylum or (ii) another form of leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417695","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-14","<p /> <p>There is comprehensive legislation in England and Wales to deal with knife crime. Unlawful possession of a knife or offensive weapon in a public place without good reason or lawful excuse is already a serious criminal offence, which carries a maximum four year custodial sentence.</p><p> </p><p>Following the commencement in July of the relevant provisions in the Criminal Justice and Courts Act 2015, offenders convicted of a second offence of possession of a knife or offensive weapon and sentenced on or after 17 July 2015 face a minimum custodial sentence of six months, or four months if a young offender aged 16 or 17. The provisions of this Act make it absolutely clear that cautions should no longer be used for serious offences such as those involving a knife or offensive weapon.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-14T15:00:43.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417695/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417695/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to tackle knife crime; and if he will bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit the carrying of a knife.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417696","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>UK Visas &amp; Immigration responds to enquiries on immigration cases raised by all levels of elected representatives and peers. The Home Office recommends that constituents with immigration enquiries use their Member of Parliament for the speediest response through one of UKVIâs six MP Account Management teams across the UK.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-17T11:25:46.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417696/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417696/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Asylum: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's policy is on (a) receiving representations and (b) entering into correspondence with Members of the Scottish Parliament on behalf of constituents who are seeking asylum in the UK.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","9409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417697","Home Office","false","2015-09-11","<p>We have not undertaken any assessment of how individual police forces respond to reported burglaries. This Government are clear that all crimes reported to the police should be taken seriously, investigated and, where appropriate, taken through the courts and met with tough sentences. Decisions on individual investigations are an operational matter for chief constables, based on the evidence available to them.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-11T14:41:18.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417697/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417697/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Burglary: Criminal Investigation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of pilot schemes undertaken by regional police forces to limit the resources available for the investigation of burglaries.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","9417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417698","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>We intend to resettle up to 20,000 Syrians in need of protection during this Parliament. We will continue to work closely with the UNHCR to identify appropriate cases, prioritising the most vulnerable. As the expanded scheme is based on need and reliant on the UNHCR and other partners to deliver, it is not possible or appropriate to set any sort of annual target, but we are clear that we want to help as many people as we can as quickly as possible.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","9413","2015-09-17T15:47:25.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417698/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417698/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the number of refugees that the Government expects to receive under the expanded Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme before the end of this calendar year.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","9418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417699","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>Female genital mutilation (FGM) is a crime. We will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls. On 22 July, the Government marked the first anniversary of the Girl Summit â the first global summit to mobilise domestic and international efforts to end FGM and child and forced marriage within a generation. All of the commitments made at the Summit have now been delivered, with Home Office commitments including:</p><p>â¢ a new mandatory reporting duty, provided for in the Serious Crime Act 2015 and due to commence in October this year, which will require specified professionals to report âknownâ cases of FGM to the police;</p><p>â¢ the launch of the Home Officeâs FGM Unit, which provides outreach support to local areas and works with the police, voluntary and community sector, survivors and professionals to develop policies and practices to end FGM;</p><p>â¢ providing resources for frontline professionals, including: a resource pack, e-learning, and distributing over 440,000 communication materials; and</p><p>â¢ the launch of a force level inspection by Her Majestyâs Inspectorate of Constabulary on the police response to âhonourâ based violence, including FGM, to help ensure the enforcement is as good as it can be. Ministers signed a cross-Government declaration outlining this progress and reaffirming this Governmentâs commitment to tackling this appalling crime.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-14T15:22:37.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417699/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417699/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent steps her Department has taken to tackle female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417700","Home Office","false","2015-09-11","<p>In 2010, we ring-fenced nearly Â£40 million of stable funding up to 2015 to provide services for victims of violence against women and girls. The Home Office contribution amounted to Â£28 million over the period.</p><p>This funding provided for Independent Domestic Violence Advisers, Independent Sexual Violence Advisers, Multi-Agency Risk Assessment Conference (MARAC) coordinators, Young Peopleâs Advocates and financial support to free phone national help lines.</p><p>The Government has committed to continuing that funding to April 2016, and has provided additional funding for both types of support services including Â£10 million for refuges, Â£3 million for domestic violence services including refuge provision and Â£7 million for victims of sexual violence and child sexual abuse.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-11T14:42:48.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417700/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417700/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Domestic Abuse and Sexual Offences: Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what funding her Department has allocated to each type of domestic and sexual violence support services in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","9392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417701","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK and French Governments have been working closely together to address the situation in Northern France. The Joint Declaration signed by the Home Secretary and the French Interior Minister on 20 August builds on the earlier declaration of September 2014 and cements a comprehensive programme of work between our two countries. Additional French police â along with extra fencing, search dogs and other security measures provided by the UK â are bolstering security at the ports of Calais and Coquelles against clandestine activity.</p><p>The new Joint Declaration contains formalised arrangements on intelligence-sharing and prosecutions to target the organised immigration crime gangs and a new command and control centre in Calais where UK and French law enforcement agencies will co-ordinate operations. Other new measures include substantial further security and physical infrastructure improvements, extra private security personnel, around-the-clock searching, additional French mobile policing units and further joint work to return economic migrants to their home countries.</p><p>In recognition that the pressure of immigration does not begin in Calais, the Declaration sets out support to frontline EU member states in ensuring fully functioning external borders and to crack down on the organised crime gangs smuggling people into Europe. A copy of the Declaration can be found at</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/455162/Joint_declaration_20_August_2015.pdf</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:55:57.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417701/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417701/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Illegal Immigrants: France","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to reduce the level of illegal immigration from Calais into the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","9371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417702","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The number of people who have had their British citizenship revoked in each quarter since Q1 2010 is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Quarter</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Q1</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Q2</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Q3</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Q4</strong></p></td><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Totals</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(Jan -Mar)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(Apr - Jun)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(Jul - Sep)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(Oct - Dec)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>19</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015*</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Information supplied in respect of 2015 is for the period January to June only.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-14T15:20:15.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417702/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417702/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","British Nationality","