"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417722","Attorney General","false","2015-09-15","<p>The payment of witness expenses and allowances to prosecution witnesses, where the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) is the prosecuting authority, is governed by the Crown Prosecution Service (Witnessesâ etc. Allowances) Regulations 1988.</p><p>The rates payable in accordance with the Regulations are designed to provide compensation to witnesses attending court but not necessarily full reimbursement of all costs incurred, including loss of earnings, whether the witness is employed or self-employed. The aim is to strike a balance between providing a reasonable level of compensation to witnesses and ensuring that public money is spent appropriately.</p><p>It is important that the allowances are set at a level that does not discourage the public from coming forward to give evidence and rates are subject to regular review. Nevertheless, limits on the amounts payable are necessary if the Government is to maintain control over public spending in order to direct limited resources to areas of greatest need.</p><p>The witness allowance rates are due to be reviewed shortly.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-09-15T14:57:17.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417722/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417722/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-09-08","Witnesses: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of reimbursing self-employed witnesses for loss of earnings when they are obliged to attend court.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","9623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417723","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-20","<p>Crime is falling but offenders committing serious offences are more likely to go to prison and for longer. Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, taking into account the maximum penalty for the offence, the relevant sentencing guidelines and all the individual facts of each case. Where the offender has recent and relevant previous convictions this is a statutory aggravating factor which should increase the severity of the sentence. In addition, a third conviction for a domestic burglary has a minimum sentence of three yearsâ imprisonment. Since December 2012 an automatic life sentence applies to any offender convicted of a second very serious sexual crime. Also, since December 2012, threatening with a knife or bladed article in a school or public place has a minimum sentence of six monthsâ imprisonment, or four monthsâ detention for a 16 or 17 year old offender. Since 17 July 2015, adult offenders convicted of a second or subsequent offence of possession of a knife or offensive weapon will face a minimum sentence of six monthsâ imprisonment.</p><br /><p>The table below shows the highest number of previous convictions of an offender convicted of the same offence and the sentence received for the most recent offence in England and Wales, 2005 â 2014.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-11-20T14:35:24.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417723/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417723/answer","9633 table.xls","Number of previous convictions from 2005-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417723/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Reoffenders: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answers of 21 July 2015 to Questions 6745, 6746, 6747, 6748, 6749 and 6750, what the length was of each custodial sentence handed down; and which courts imposed the non-immediate custodial sentences referred to in those Answers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417724","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p>According to TV Licensing's data, in 2014 232,290 women and 114,347 men were interviewed under caution by TV Licensing officers in the course of investigating TV licence offences.</p><p> </p><p>The number of people prosecuted for licence fee evasion in 2014 is published here: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428943/cjs-outcomes-by-offence-data-tool.xls" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428943/cjs-outcomes-by-offence-data-tool.xls</a> From âoffenceâ drop down list select 191A Television licence evasion. From âsexâ drop down list select the male or female.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014 11 men and 28 women were committed to prison for non-payment of a fine where the registered fine was for non-payment of the TV Licence. The average time spent in prison was 18 days for men and 20 days for women.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","9560","2015-09-16T10:42:03.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417724/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417724/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) men and (b) women were committed to prison for the non-payment of a fine for a television licence offence in the most recent year for which information is available; and how many days each such offender spent in prison.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417725","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-11","<p>We have specifically protected legal aid (both for initial advice and representation), subject to the statutory means and merits tests, for civil legal services provided in relation to contravention of the Equality Act 2010. Publicly funded advice continues to be available for Employment Tribunal discrimination claims, and publicly funded advice and representation is available in the Employment Appeal Tribunal. This therefore includes funding for new and expectant mothers who may have experienced discrimination.</p><p> </p><p>Legal aid is a demand-led scheme and funding will be provided wherever the statutory tests are met. The Department does not allocate a specific amount in advance.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-11T13:45:51.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417725/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417725/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Employment: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much funding his Department has allocated in 2015-16 for the provision of specialist legal advice and representation to new and expectant mothers who may have experienced unlawful discrimination at work.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","9651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417726","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p>Police forces use local systems to record offences committed on bail, and there is no requirement to report data centrally. The complete information can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","9557 ; 9657","2015-09-16T15:08:21.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417726/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417726/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Bail: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2015 to Question 4115, what the reasons are for the reduction between 2010 and 2014 in the figures contained in the tables in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417727","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p>Police forces use local systems to record offences committed on bail, and there is no requirement to report data centrally. The complete information can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","9557 ; 9620","2015-09-16T15:08:21.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417727/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417727/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Bail: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2015 to Question 4115, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the reductions in those figures between 2010 and 2014.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417728","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-11","<p>The law relating to contempt of court applies generally to all courts and this includes the family court. The legislation establishing the family court provides that the family court may make any order (including orders punishing for contempt of court) that could be made by the High Court or the county court if the proceedings were in those respective courts; and the powers of judges in the family court to punish for contempt are proportionate to their level of seniority.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-11T13:42:28.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417728/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417728/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Family Courts: Contempt of Court","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reason contempt of court laws do not apply in the family court.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","9404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417729","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>In a single financial year, the Department expected to receive income from employment tribunal fees of Â£10m. In the first full year following introduction, the Department collected Â£9m, broadly in line with expectations.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-11T13:19:27.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417729/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417729/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department (a) expected to receive and (b) received from employment tribunal fees in the year following the introduction of the scheme.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","9462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417730","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>On 11 June we announced the start of the post-implementation review of the introduction of fees in the Employment Tribunals on the Ministry of Justice website. We have received a range of views and evidence from a variety of sources and are giving all relevant material the appropriate consideration.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-11T13:40:51.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417730/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417730/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he will publish his Department's review of employment tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","9463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417731","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department does not hold information requested. Annual costs of administering employment tribunal fee remission applications and annual administration costs of the employment tribunal fee scheme form part of the wider costs of operating and administering the Employment Tribunals. In 2014/15, the full cost for operating the Employment Tribunalsâ was Â£71.4m.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","9492","2015-09-11T12:23:51.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417731/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417731/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the annual cost of administering employment tribunal fee remission applications.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","9464"
