"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416957","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Department published the names of the Advisory Group members, as well as their principal roles, both current and former, in July 2015. This information is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Advisory Group Member</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Current or former role</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dawn Airey</p></td><td><p>Senior Vice President of Yahooâs business in Europe, the Middle East and Africa and formerly Chairman and Chief Executive of Channel 5.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dame Colette Bowe</p></td><td><p>Chairman of the Banking Standards Board, President of the Voice of the Listener and Viewer and former Chair of Ofcom.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Andrew Fisher</p></td><td><p>Executive Chairman at Shazam.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Darren Henley OBE</p><p> </p></td><td><p>CEO of Arts Council England and former Managing Director of Classic FM.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ashley Highfield</p></td><td><p>CEO of Johnston Press, one of the largest local media groups in the UK, and former director at the BBC.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Alex Mahon</p></td><td><p>Former CEO of Shine Group, global television content production company.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lopa Patel MBE</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>Digital entrepreneur and founder/CEO of NewAsianPost.com and Diversity UK.</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stewart Purvis OBE</p></td><td><p>British broadcaster and academic, and former Editor-in-Chief and CEO of ITN.</p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Group has no legal status or powers and no decision-making or research commissioning functions. These are not public appointments and therefore the Group is not subject to the Cabinet Office guidelines for public appointments.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL1874 ; HL1875","2015-09-16T16:25:33.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416957/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416957/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the BBC Charter renewal advisory panel will have the power to commission research; and, if so, from whom.","false","Biography information for Baroness Grender",,"Baroness Grender","HL1877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416958","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-14","<p>The BBC Charter Review Consultation, published on 16 July 2015, drew heavily on the evidence heard by, and the report from, the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committeeâs report on the Future of the BBC. The Charter Review provides an opportunity for a wide-ranging national debate about the BBC, and will inform the Governmentâs proposals for the future of the BBC, including its funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-14T14:42:21.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416958/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416958/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the conclusions of the House of Commons Culture, Media and Sport Committee report of February 2015, <i>Future of the BBC</i>, that (1) the BBCâs independence could be compromised by negotiations with government that lack transparency and public consultation; (2) licence fee payers must be consulted and Parliament should have an opportunity to debate any significant changes to funding responsibilities; and (3) that it was wholly wrong that the 2010 licence fee settlement was not subject to any public or parliamentary consultation.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL1878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416959","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government has not performed, and does not intend to perform, a retrospective assessment of bills introduced over the last Parliament because under the Governmentâs proposals on English Votes for English Laws, the application of the proposed new rules to future legislation will be a matter for the Speaker of the House of Commons. Decisions on certification will be a matter for Parliament and will apply to future legislation. Moreover, the Government's proposals would apply to England and England and Wales-only provisions within bills, as well as bills that are England-only in their entirety.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston","HL1880","2015-09-21T14:49:26.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416959/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416959/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Bills: England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Stowell of Beeston on 29 July (HL1727), whether they plan to conduct an assessment of the number of bills in each of the three most recent parliamentary Sessions that affected England alone and had no implications for any of the other nations in the United Kingdom; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416960","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government has not performed, and does not intend to perform, a retrospective assessment of bills introduced over the last Parliament because under the Governmentâs proposals on English Votes for English Laws, the application of the proposed new rules to future legislation will be a matter for the Speaker of the House of Commons. Decisions on certification will be a matter for Parliament and will apply to future legislation. Moreover, the Government's proposals would apply to England and England and Wales-only provisions within bills, as well as bills that are England-only in their entirety.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston","HL1879","2015-09-21T14:49:26.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416960/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416960/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Bills: England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Stowell of Beeston on 29 July (HL1727), why they have not conducted an assessment of the number of bills in each of the previous five Parliaments that affected England alone and had no implications for any of the other nations in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416961","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government does not plan to produce an impact assessment for its proposals, which relate to House of Commons procedure. However, given the importance of the Governmentâs proposed changes, the Leader of the House of Commons has invited the Procedure Committee to review the proposals in operation in order that there is proper scrutiny.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston",,"2015-09-21T14:44:49.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416961/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416961/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","English Votes for English Laws","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Stowell of Beeston on 29 July (HL1727), whether they plan to produce an impact assessment of their proposals for English Votes for English Laws; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416962","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-14","<p>The BBC Charter Review Advisory Groupâs terms of reference are:</p><p>Membership of the Group is voluntary and by invitation from the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, who will Chair the meetings.</p><p>Members will possess a range of skills, experience and expertise that enables them to contribute independently and in different ways to the oversight of the Governmentâs Review of the BBC Royal Charter.</p><p>Members are appointed on the basis of their personal experience not as representatives of their respective organisations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further details on the BBC Charter Review Advisory Group can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445912/TERMS_OF_REFERENCE.pdf.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-14T14:50:30.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416962/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416962/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what are the terms of reference of the BBC Charter renewal advisory panel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury",,"Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury","HL1882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416963","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The members of the Charter Review Advisory Group were appointed by invitation from the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport. The Group is not a decision-making body, and forms one part of a wider Charter Review process which includes public consultation. As set out in the published terms of reference, additional members may be co-opted as and when required by the Chairman. Members of the Group act in a voluntary capacity and on the basis of their personal experience and expertise rather than as representatives of their respective organisations.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-16T16:25:56.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416963/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416963/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government by what process the members of the BBC Charter renewal advisory panel were appointed.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury",,"Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury","HL1883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416964","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-14","<p>In its consideration of policy and process issues for the Charter Review, it is envisaged that the Advisory Group will consider a range of sources of evidence â including, but not limited to, responses to the Governmentâs consultation, and publicly available sources of evidence such as the BBCâs strategy documents. There are no current plans for evidence, written or oral, to be taken in public by the Advisory Group.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-14T14:52:09.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416964/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416964/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the BBC Charter renewal advisory panel will take evidence during the course of its work; and if so, whether that evidence will be taken in public.","false","Biography information for Lord Clement-Jones",,"Lord Clement-Jones","HL1884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416965","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-14","<p>There are currently no such plans. The Group may make recommendations about policy and process, but ultimate responsibility for decisions remains with Department for Culture, Media and Sport Ministers.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-14T14:51:01.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416965/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416965/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they plan to publish the views and advice they receive from the members of the BBC Charter renewal advisory panel.","false","Biography information for Lord Clement-Jones",,"Lord Clement-Jones","HL1885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416966","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-14","<p>In its consideration of policy and process issues for the Charter Review, it is envisaged that the Advisory Group will consider a range of sources of evidence â including, but not limited to, responses to the Governmentâs consultation, and publicly available sources of evidence such as the BBCâs strategy documents. There are no current plans for evidence, written or oral, to be taken in public by the Advisory Group.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-14T14:52:41.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416966/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416966/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the BBC Charter renewal advisory panel has the power to compel evidence from the people and institutions from whom they wish to hear.","false","Biography information for Lord Clement-Jones",,"Lord Clement-Jones","HL1886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416967","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-23","<p>We intend to publish the Report in the next few weeks.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-23T10:36:23.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416967/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416967/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Packaging","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government when they plan to publish the final report on the review of the enforcement of the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008 in respect of copycat packaging.","false","Biography information for Lord Clement-Jones",,"Lord Clement-Jones","HL1887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416968","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2015-09-17","<p /> <p>An announcement on who will lead the review, terms of reference and how it will run is expected shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-17T11:23:01.327Z","2015-09-24T13:52:58.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416968/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416968/answer",,"Baroness Neville-Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416968/answer/previousversion/21943",,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Tickets: Touting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what progress they have made in setting up the review of consumer protection measures for the secondary ticketing market.","false","Biography information for Lord Clement-Jones",,"Lord Clement-Jones","HL1888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416969","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Diabetes is a clear priority for this Government and we are in the early stages of developing plans to improve the outcomes of people with and at risk of diabetes. For example, we are considering improvements in the management and care of people with diabetes which would focus equally on Type 1 and Type 2 diabetes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Whilst there is still more to do in terms of reducing variation in the delivery of National Institute for Health and Care Excellence care processes and achievement of the treatment targets, we are now beginning to see the benefits of incentivising these through the Quality and Outcomes Framework in terms of reductions in complications and premature mortality.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The most recent National Diabetes Audit data shows that the relative risk for someone with Type 1 or Type 2 diabetes developing heart failure is significantly reduced. There are also clear trends in the reduction of the relative risk of developing angina, heart attack, stroke, major amputation and end stage kidney disease. In 2013, the Global Burden of Disease Study showed that the United Kingdom has the lowest rates of early death due to diabetes of the 19 wealthy countries included in the analysis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Diabetes Audit 2012â2013 Report 2: Complications and Mortality provides data on health outcomes for those with Type 1 diabetes and Type 2 diabetes on an annual basis allowing comparisons between the two types to be made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England is developing a sample service specification on the transition from children and young people diabetes services to adult services for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to use if they so choose. This will benefit those with Type 1 diabetes. In addition, a sample diabetes service specification was published in July 2014, which aimed to highlight the specific care needs of those with Type 1 diabetes where they differ from those with Type 2. However, NHS England currently has no plans to publish plans for a programme of work to improve outcomes for people with Type 1 diabetes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also recently agreed to extend the roll out of its Right Care programme to all CCGs over the next four years. This will ensure that, where local diabetes services and outcomes are poorer compared to demographic peers, suitable improvement programmes will be implemented, with the learning shared across all CCGs.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-17T16:20:39.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416969/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416969/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Diabetes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 21 July (HL1204), whether they plan to publish (1) their plans to improve the health outcomes of people with Type 1 diabetes; and (2) the degrees of improvement at annual intervals.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL1889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416970","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Diabetes is a clear priority for this Government and we are in the early stages of developing plans to improve the outcomes of people with and at risk of diabetes. For example, we are considering improvements in the management and care of people with diabetes which would focus equally on Type 1 and Type 2 diabetes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Whilst there is still more to do in terms of reducing variation in the delivery of National Institute for Health and Care Excellence care processes and achievement of the treatment targets, we are now beginning to see the benefits of incentivising these through the Quality and Outcomes Framework in terms of reductions in complications and premature mortality.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The most recent National Diabetes Audit data shows that the relative risk for someone with Type 1 or Type 2 diabetes developing heart failure is significantly reduced. There are also clear trends in the reduction of the relative risk of developing angina, heart attack, stroke, major amputation and end stage kidney disease. In 2013, the Global Burden of Disease Study showed that the United Kingdom has the lowest rates of early death due to diabetes of the 19 wealthy countries included in the analysis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Diabetes Audit 2012â2013 Report 2: Complications and Mortality provides data on health outcomes for those with Type 1 diabetes and Type 2 diabetes on an annual basis allowing comparisons between the two types to be made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England is developing a sample service specification on the transition from children and young people diabetes services to adult services for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to use if they so choose. This will benefit those with Type 1 diabetes. In addition, a sample diabetes service specification was published in July 2014, which aimed to highlight the specific care needs of those with Type 1 diabetes where they differ from those with Type 2. However, NHS England currently has no plans to publish plans for a programme of work to improve outcomes for people with Type 1 diabetes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also recently agreed to extend the roll out of its Right Care programme to all CCGs over the next four years. This will ensure that, where local diabetes services and outcomes are poorer compared to demographic peers, suitable improvement programmes will be implemented, with the learning shared across all CCGs.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-17T16:25:39.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416970/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416970/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Diabetes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 21 July (HL1204), what outcomes have been achieved through the incentives in the Quality and Outcomes Framework regarding the care and treatment of those with Type 1 diabetes.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL1890"
