"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416994","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-17","<p>In setting the baseline in 2013-14, the Government took into account the additional costs of delivering services in rural areas. It increased the amount distributed through sparsity in the older people's social care need formula, and both the district and county-level environmental, protective and cultural services need formulae. In addition a separate sparsity element was introduced in the fire need formula.<br><br><br>The Government believes that all authorities have sufficient resources to deliver adequate services within their areas.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-09-17T15:57:53.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416994/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416994/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Rural Areas: Local Government Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how they plan to assist rural councils that cannot access funding from the Rural Services Delivery Grant in order to ensure that the additional cost of delivery of services in rural areas is adequately resourced.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL1914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416995","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-15","<p>We have recently increased the direct payment rates for upland farmers under Pillar 1 of the Common Agricultural Policy to ensure they are distributed more equitably across all English farms. These increases will help prevent a fall in income for upland farmers following the expiry of existing support under the Uplands Entry Level Scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Upland farmers are also eligible to apply for support under the new Countryside Stewardship (CS) scheme, which is focused on improving biodiversity and water quality, mitigating flood risks and enhancing the landscape.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We will monitor the impact on upland farmers of these changes to Common Agricultural Policy support arrangements.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-15T12:17:47.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416995/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416995/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Hill Farming","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the impact of a further reduction in income for upland farmers on ecosystem services and landscape management.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL1915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416996","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is wholly committed to protecting women and girls from violence and supporting victims and survivors. We are currently developing a refreshed strategy on violence against women and girls which will include intervening earlier in the abuse cycle to deter and rehabilitate perpetrators, as well as continuing to improve the protection for victims and bring offenders to justice.</p><p>We are supportive of any tools that can assist the police to manage offenders and protect victims. The potential application of new technologies and electronic monitoring to protect victims of domestic abuse is something that we are exploring as part of our refreshed strategy and we are committed to working with police forces to test new technology. We have no immediate plans to mandate the use of electronic tagging in relation to Domestic Violence Protection Orders.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-16T12:46:09.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416996/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416996/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Electronic Tagging","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what plans they have to extend the mandation of electronic tagging to include individuals under a Domestic Violence Protection Order.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL1916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416997","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-07","<p>A comprehensive review of the Electronic Monitoring programme to introduce GPS technology is underway.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-10-07T11:28:42.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416997/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416997/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-07","Electronic Tagging","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what plans they have to extend the mandation of electronic tagging to include priority and persistent offenders as part of integrated offender management programmes.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL1917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416998","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p /> <p>A comprehensive review of the Electronic Monitoring programme to introduce GPS technology is underway.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-09-16T14:32:09.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416998/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416998/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-07","Electronic Tagging","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what plans they have to address the delays in implementing the contract for GPS electronic tagging technology.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL1918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416999","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>We engage with UN and US and EU partners about the risks and impacts of climate change on a regular basis, both within the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change negotiations, and in other fora including the G7, G20 and Pacific Island Forum. This includes, but is not limited to engagement focussing on the particular vulnerabilities of the small island states to climate change.</p><p> </p><p>The UK provides financial support to small island nations through bilateral and multilateral channels, such as the European Development Fund, World Bank, International Monetary Fund and regional development banks. The UK has also committed to provide financial support to the multilateral Green Climate Fund which will include support for adaptation in countries vulnerable to the adverse effects of climate change, including the small island states.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL1920","2015-09-18T12:01:28.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416999/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416999/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Pacific Ocean Islands: Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assistance they are providing to (1) Tuvalu, (2) Vanuatu, and (3) Nauru, to counter the threat to the long-term viability of the islands caused by climate change.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL1919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417000","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>We engage with UN and US and EU partners about the risks and impacts of climate change on a regular basis, both within the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change negotiations, and in other fora including the G7, G20 and Pacific Island Forum. This includes, but is not limited to engagement focussing on the particular vulnerabilities of the small island states to climate change.</p><p> </p><p>The UK provides financial support to small island nations through bilateral and multilateral channels, such as the European Development Fund, World Bank, International Monetary Fund and regional development banks. The UK has also committed to provide financial support to the multilateral Green Climate Fund which will include support for adaptation in countries vulnerable to the adverse effects of climate change, including the small island states.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL1919","2015-09-18T12:01:28.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417000/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417000/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Islands: Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what discussions they have had with (1) other European Union member states, (2) the United States of America, and (3) the United Nations, regarding the threat posed by climate change to the viability of small island nations.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL1920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417001","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-15","<p>The UK Government has not lifted a ban on neonicotinoids. There is not a ban, but a restriction on the use of three neonicotinoids in place since 1 December 2013. A number of uses remain approved. The restriction has been implemented in full.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The main European regulation on pesticides provides for limited and controlled use of the restricted neonicotinoids on an exceptional basis to control a danger which cannot be contained by any other reasonable means.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government considers applications for such emergency authorisations according to the legal requirements and the best available scientific evidence. The UK Expert Committee on Pesticides advises Ministers on what authorisations are capable of being issued. The Committee considered two applications for emergency authorisations, each for two separate neonicotinoid seed treatments for winter oilseed rape this year. They recommended the first application, which requested authorisation to use neonicotinoids on 79% of the national crop area, should be rejected as their use was not limited and controlled. They recommended that the second application, to use neonicotinoids on 5% of the national crop area, should be accepted as the use was limited and controlled, was subject to stewardship arrangements and was to control a danger which could not be contained by any other reasonable means.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Committeeâs advice has been published online and copies will be placed in the House Libraries.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The European Commission has begun a review of the science on neonicotinoids and pollinators. The Government will participate fully in that process.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-15T12:19:26.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417001/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417001/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Neonicotinoids","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government on what scientific evidence they based their decision to lift the ban on neonicotinoids.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL1921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417002","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>While Greece remains in the euro, its financial stability is the responsibility of the euro area. Ministers and officials routinely meet with international counterparts to discuss economic and financial issues within the euro area and wider European Union, including ongoing financial assistance programmes.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-09-21T15:30:11.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417002/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417002/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Economic Situation: Greece","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government when they are next meeting representatives of other European Union member states to discuss the procedures in the Greek emergency financial recovery plan.","false","Biography information for Lord Dykes",,"Lord Dykes","HL1922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417003","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the roads are safe for all road users. The European Union has required improved mirrors on new models of heavy goods vehicle launched after 30 June 2014. ãFurtherãchanges are expected in due course, to allow camera monitoring systems and the redesign of lorry cabs for better vision.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are also watching closely the impact of Transport for London's proposals in this area, including the Safer Lorry Scheme.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-16T13:29:25.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417003/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417003/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-07","Cycling: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what plans they have to help protect cyclists from collisions with heavy goods vehicles caused by the driver being unable to see the cyclist on the near side.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417004","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>Updated guidance for competent authorities was published on 31 July 2015 to reflect the extension of the National Referral Mechanism to identify and support all victims of modern slavery in England and Wales. This guidance now includes information on the definitions and nature of all forms of modern slavery. On the same day, similar updates were also published to the guidance for frontline workers on identifying victims of modern slavery.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-14T15:23:31.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417004/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417004/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 20 July (HL1460), whether the guidance for competent authorities will be revised to include indicators of slavery, servitude, and forced or compulsory labour, in accordance with the Modern Slavery Act 2015 and Article 4 of the European Convention on Human Rights, as distinct from cases of human trafficking for these forms of exploitation; and if so, when that guidance will be produced.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417005","Home Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>In 2013/14, 1,282 referrals were made into the NRM, of which 537 were accommodated in NASS accommodation. Of those in NASS accommodation, 403 individuals were issued with Positive Reasonable Grounds decisions, of which 154 received a subsequent positive Conclusive Ground decision.</p><p>In 2013/15 1,800 referrals were made into the NRM, of which 716 were accommodated in NASS accommodation. Of those in NASS accommodation, 632 individuals were issued with Positive Reasonable Grounds decisions, of which 126 received a subsequent positive Conclusive Ground decision.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-15T14:24:18.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417005/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417005/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Human Trafficking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, in (1) 2013â14, and (2) 2014â15, how many potential victims of trafficking referred to the National Referral Mechanism (NRM) were accommodated by the National Asylum Support Service; and of those, how many received (a) a positive reasonable grounds decision, and (b) a positive conclusive grounds decision.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417006","Home Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The number of potential victims of human trafficking who received outreach support under the Victim Care Contract whilst accommodated through the Home Office asylum contracts accommodation were as follows:</p><p>01/07/2013 - 30/06/2014 - 202 (Male - 20; Female - 182)</p><p>01/07/2014 - 30/06/2015 - 246 (Male - 33: Female - 213)</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-14T15:24:16.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417006/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417006/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Human Trafficking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government in (1) 2013â14 and (2) 2014â15 how many potential victims of trafficking referred to the National Referral Mechanism and accommodated by the National Asylum Support Service received specialist trafficking outreach support under the Victim Care Contract during the 45-day reflection and recovery periods.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417007","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-09-11T13:55:38.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417007/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417007/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","Carer's Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many households in receipt of Carerâs Allowance have a total benefit income above (1) Â£20,000,and (2) Â£23,000.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL1927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417008","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A copy of the impact assessment is attached.</p>",,"Lord Freud","HL1929","2015-09-14T13:27:33.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417008/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417008/answer","Benefit CAp Impact Assessmet.pdf","Benefit Cap Impact Assessment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417008/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","Social Security Benefits: Carers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their estimate of the number of carers who will be affected by the reduction of the benefit cap to (1) Â£20,000 per year outside London, and (2) Â£23,000 per year in London.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL1928"
