"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417010","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is currently finalising the detailed design for trialling new traffic signs, displaying comparative motorway fuel prices, to provide greater transparency on the pricing of fuel at service areas and to encourage competition. The first sign will be installed this Winter, with the remaining three signs by Spring 2016.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-16T13:43:32.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417010/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417010/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-07","Motorway Service Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what plans they have to encourage motorway service station signs to advertise on approaching road signs the brand and prices of fuel they are selling.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417011","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-21","<p /> <p>Ahead of the introduction of the new State Pension in April 2016, we are specifically encouraging people to find out how they could increase their new State Pension, including through National Insurance credits. This includes encouraging people who are eligible but may not be claiming carerâs credits at the moment. We are working with the media, local authorities, the NHS, voluntary organisations and charities, including carersâ organisations to promote material, including fact sheets and videos, ensuring the right information and advice is available on carerâs credits.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information that would allow us to identify individuals who might be eligible for the carerâs credit. We use a range of methods to signpost the carerâs credit to individuals who contact us about other benefits who might be potentially eligible, including when someone has claimed but is not entitled to Carerâs Allowance. Departmental officials promote the carerâs credit at carersâ events, including Carerâs Week, and amongst support organisations. Information on the credits is available on the governmentâs website GOV.UK and also on carersâ organisations websites.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1932","2015-09-21T14:47:53.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417011/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417011/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","National Insurance Credits: Carers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what further steps they propose to encourage up-take of Carerâs Credit by those who are caring for others for 20 hours or more per week and who do not qualify for Carerâs Allowance.","false","Biography information for Lord Kirkwood of Kirkhope",,"Lord Kirkwood of Kirkhope","HL1931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417012","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-21","<p>Ahead of the introduction of the new State Pension in April 2016, we are specifically encouraging people to find out how they could increase their new State Pension, including through National Insurance credits. This includes encouraging people who are eligible but may not be claiming carerâs credits at the moment. We are working with the media, local authorities, the NHS, voluntary organisations and charities, including carersâ organisations to promote material, including fact sheets and videos, ensuring the right information and advice is available on carerâs credits.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information that would allow us to identify individuals who might be eligible for the carerâs credit. We use a range of methods to signpost the carerâs credit to individuals who contact us about other benefits who might be potentially eligible, including when someone has claimed but is not entitled to Carerâs Allowance. Departmental officials promote the carerâs credit at carersâ events, including Carerâs Week, and amongst support organisations. Information on the credits is available on the governmentâs website GOV.UK and also on carersâ organisations websites.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1931","2015-09-21T14:47:53.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417012/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417012/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","National Insurance Credits: Carers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they plan to assess all data held by the Department for Work and Pensions to identify those who may be eligible for Carerâs Credit with a view to introducing a media campaign to increase public awareness of entitlement to it.","false","Biography informati