"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417056","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The requested information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Budget Statement on 18 March 2015, the Government announced that from April 2016 all central government departments and their arm's length bodies will be required to publish, on a quarterly basis, all interest liable under the late payment legislation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The 2015 Public Contracts Regulations introduced a reporting requirement so that from 2016 contracting authorities will have to publish details of the amount of interest paid due to late payment and from 2017 they will have to publish their liability to interest whether or not paid.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1977","2015-09-21T15:13:48.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417056/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417056/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Billing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many compensation awards were given under section 5A of the Late Payment of Commercial Debts (Interest) Act 1998 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL1976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417057","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The requested information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Budget Statement on 18 March 2015, the Government announced that from April 2016 all central government departments and their arm's length bodies will be required to publish, on a quarterly basis, all interest liable under the late payment legislation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The 2015 Public Contracts Regulations introduced a reporting requirement so that from 2016 contracting authorities will have to publish details of the amount of interest paid due to late payment and from 2017 they will have to publish their liability to interest whether or not paid.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1976","2015-09-21T15:13:48.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417057/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417057/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Billing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many claims for compensation under section 5A of the Late Payment of Commercial Debts (Interest) Act 1998 were made against (1) local authorities, (2) NHS providers, including Clinical Commissioning Groups, (3) non-departmental public bodies and (4) government departments, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL1977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417058","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-15","<p /> <p>The Department for Work and Pensions conducts thorough identity, immigration status, and right to work checks on all applications for National Insurance Numbers.</p><p> </p><p>The Department works closely with the Home Office to identify anyone with no valid right to reside or work in the UK and an applicant who could not demonstrate that they were in this country legally would not be given a National Insurance Number.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-09-15T11:23:47.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417058/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417058/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","National Insurance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what checks are made to ensure that applicants are entitled to (1) reside within the United Kingdom, and (2) work within the United Kingdom, before new National Insurance numbers are issued.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL1978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417059","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-14","<p /> <p>According to the German National Statistics Agency there were 103,756 UK nationals resident in Germany as of 31 December 2014.</p><p> </p><p>According to the German Federal Employment Agency, in 2014, there were 33,536 UK nationals in regular employment in Germany and paying national insurance contributions.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on the number of UK nationals claiming social benefits in Germany are not held.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-09-14T14:12:21.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417059/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417059/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","British Nationals Abroad: Germany","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what estimates they have made, if any, either from United Kingdom sources or from access to German statistics, of the number of United Kingdom citizens (1) resident in Germany, (2) working in Germany,â¯and (3) claiming social benefits in Germany.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL1979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417060","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1981 ; HL1983","2015-09-17T12:48:00.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417060/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417060/answer","Lord Wallace of Saltaire UKSA reply.pdf","UK Statistics Reply ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417060/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what estimates they have made of the number of United Kingdom citizens resident within the rest of the European Union; and what level of confidence they have of the accuracy of that estimate.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL1980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417061","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1980 ; HL1983","2015-09-17T12:48:00.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417061/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417061/answer","Lord Wallace of Saltaire UKSA reply.pdf","UK Statistics Reply ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417061/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Overseas Workers: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what estimates they have made of the number of United Kingdom citizens currently employed within the rest of the European Union; and what level of confidence they have of the accuracy of that estimate.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL1981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417062","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-23","<p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The information requested is not available. Currently net migration of students is measured via the International Passenger Survey (IPS) which estimates volumes of students arriving and leaving, based on their stated main reason for entering the UK at time of arrival (which may not correspond with their visa) and their stated answer to the question of why they originally came to the UK when surveyed at the time of departure. It does not measure the type of institution attended, the level of course studied, whether the student graduated or how long it has been between finishing the course and departing from the UK. Once exit check data are available (from Autumn/ Winter 2015), it may be possible to start using visa data to estimate the balance of those coming, those staying legitimately and those departing. However to get a full picture may take several years and will depend heavily on the ability to match the exit data with visa data. The data will not take into account whether a student graduated or not.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-23T10:35:51.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417062/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417062/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what estimates they have made of the proportion of international students from outside the European Union who have graduated from United Kingdom universities between 2005 and 2010 who remained within the United Kingdom (1) one year, (2) two years, and (3) five years, after graduation.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL1982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417063","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1980 ; HL1981","2015-09-17T12:48:00.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417063/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417063/answer","Lord Wallace of Saltaire UKSA reply.pdf","UK Statistics Reply ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417063/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what estimate they have made of the number of United Kingdom citizens resident outside the European Union; how many of those citizens they estimate to hold dual nationality; and what level of confidence they have of the accuracy of those estimates.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL1983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417064","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-16","<p>The installed generating capacities of each power station and expressed as a percentage of total UK generation capacity are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Power Station</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Installed Capacity (MW)*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage of total UK Generating Capacity*</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Longannet</p></td><td><p>2260</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ferrybridge</p></td><td><p>980</p></td><td><p>1.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ironbridge</p></td><td><p>360</p></td><td><p>0.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Eggborough</p></td><td><p>1960</p></td><td><p>2.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lynemouth</p></td><td><p>420</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rugeley</p></td><td><p>1006</p></td><td><p>1.2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>*Source:</em><em> Chapter 5.10 Digest of United Kingdom Energy Statistics (DUKES) <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/electricity-chapter-5-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/electricity-chapter-5-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes</a></em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Decisions on plant closures are a commercial matter for individual plant owners. The owners of Longannet and Ferrybridge have publicly stated their intention to close these plants by 1 April 2016. Ironbridge is required to close by end 2015 under the requirements of the Large Combustion Plant Directive. The owner of Eggborough has announced the plant may cease generating at the end of March 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-09-16T14:55:03.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417064/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417064/answer","DUKES_2015_Chapter_5.pdf","Chapter 5 Digest of UK Energy Stats (DUKES)","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417064/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-07","Power Stations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is the peak generating capacity of (1) Longannet, (2) Ferrybridge, (3) Ironbridge, (4) Eggborough, (5) Lynemouth and (6) Rugeley power stations; what percentage of the total generating capacity of the United Kingdom each one represents; and when those power stations are expected to close.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL1984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417065","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>Even with the removal of pre-accreditation we are currently on track to deliver at least 30% of our electricity from renewable sources by 2020. In 2014, renewablesâ share of electricity generation was 19.1% on an unadjusted basis.</p><p>The UK is also continuing to make progress towards the 2020 renewables target of 15% of final energy consumption from renewable sources. We are on track to meet the next interim target, which is an average of final energy consumption over 2013/14. The provisional figure, released on 25 June, showed 6.3% of final energy consumption for 2013/14 came from renewable sources, against a target level of 5.4%.</p><p>In order to meet the 2050 target (80% reduction on 1990 level) we know we will need significant cuts in emissions across all parts of the economy by 2050. We will need a balanced mix of low carbon technologies, including nuclear, Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) and renewables, to help tackle the threat of climate change while keeping the lights on and ensuring the best value for consumers.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-09-14T14:34:18.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417065/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417065/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-07","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the impact that remaining pre-accreditation from the feed-in tariff scheme will have on the United Kingdomâs ability to meet its climate change targets.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL1985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417066","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) is responsible for ensuring that it and its delivery partners (the Site Licence Companies) have the right skills and capability to deliver its mission. The Department monitors closely the work of the NDA â a specialist contracting authority - and its contractors, which manage and operate the sites on its behalf.</p><p>The current NDA team bring decades of technical and commercial experience to the oversight of these major contracts and the Department is assured that the NDA has the necessary resource and expertise to oversee work at Sellafield and its other sites.</p><p>In light of the decision, announced by the Secretary of State in January 2015, to change the ownership model for Sellafield, bringing the Sellafield Ltd Site Licence Company under the direct ownership of the NDA as a wholly owned subsidiary with effect from April 2016, the NDA is re-assessing its future resource requirements. The model change has prioritised accessing world class capabilities to all levels of the site.</p><p>Performance at Sellafield has been improving steadily since the NDA took ownership in 2005, prior to which there was little investment in the legacy infrastructure and no progress with decommissioning. Sellafield Ltd has on average met 86% of its milestones in recent years and is making good progress against its work plan for 2015/16.</p><p>The NDA publishes reports on its website on progress on priority programmes and projects. The latest version of the document can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nda.gov.uk/publication/programmes-and-major-projects-report-pilot-3/" target="_blank">http://www.nda.gov.uk/publication/programmes-and-major-projects-report-pilot-3/</a></p><p>An update is scheduled for later this Autumn.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-09-14T14:32:45.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417066/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417066/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-07","Sellafield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of whether the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority has sufficient human resources of the necessary calibre and expertise to ensure that construction work at Sellafield is being effectively managed and supervised; whether that work is on course to meet all the necessary deadlines; and what progress has been made with that work.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417067","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","As required by UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 2139, the Secretary General has produced monthly reports to the Security Council on the humanitarian situation in Syria. UNSCR 2165 and its successor, UNSCR 2191, also continue to be implemented. According to the UN Secretary Generalâs most recent report, by 31 July 2015, the UN and its partners had delivered 154 shipments of aid into Syria. The UK has allocated Â£233 million for the provision of humanitarian assistance inside Syria, to be delivered through our UN and non-governmental organisation partners. However, the delivery of aid in Syria is complicated by the continued obstruction of aid delivery by the Assad regime, as well as by the regimeâs indiscriminate attacks on population centres, especially through the use of barrel bombs. Countries with influence over the Syrian government, including Russia, must use that influence to press the Assad regime to comply with its responsibilities under international humanitarian and human rights law.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:20:38.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417067/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417067/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what progress has been made on the implementation of UN Security Council Resolutions 2139 and 2165 regarding Syria, in particular regarding the action or inaction of the governments of Russia and China.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417068","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-21","<p>The UK is committed to supporting the most vulnerable people in need inside Syria wherever they are, in accordance with international humanitarian principles. The UK co-sponsored and lobbied hard for UN Security Council Resolutions 2165 and 2191 which enable the UN to deliver aid across border, without the consent of the regime, to assist those in the hardest to reach areas.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-09-21T15:10:02.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417068/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417068/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-07","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they have taken to improve access for humanitarian agencies to deliver aid to civilian populations in Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417069","Home Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>The UK works with a range of international partners to combat the flow of illicit drugs. We do so to tackle the international drugs trade and minimise the threat it poses to the UK and its citizens. The UK Government takes its domestic and international human rights obligations seriously. We remain opposed to the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and are consistent in our communication with international partners on this issue. Promoting and safeguarding human rights is, and will remain, a fundamental component of our international work.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-15T14:44:23.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417069/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417069/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they have taken steps to ensure that any funding they provide to counter-narcotics schemes in other countries, including Iran, Pakistan and The Gambia, promotes the removal of the death penalty.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417070","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>For clarity, the costs referred to here are for the preparation and consideration of proposals for boundary variations to the Lake District and Yorkshire Dales National Parks.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The costs to Defra to date, including for the public inquiry, are Â£122,360. This includes Planning Inspectorate costs, the cost of an inquiry manager, notice of the inquiry, and the costs of venues for the inquiry. In addition, there are costs of staff time which have not been quantified.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The estimated costs to Natural England are Â£490,000 since 2009. This includes the costs of extensive technical assessments of the areas concerned and the production of detailed reports, public and statutory consultations, printing costs, and the costs to Natural England of the public inquiry. It does not include staff costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been made of any funding and resources expended by the third sector.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-17T11:13:31.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417070/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417070/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","National Parks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their estimate of the amount of government, public-sector and third-sector funding and resources expended so far on preparing for and considering the revision of National Park boundaries.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417071","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>Following the public inquiry into proposals to extend the Lake District and Yorkshire Dales National Parks, the inspector has submitted his report to Defra. The Secretary of State is considering the report and will issue her decisions in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-17T11:15:23.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417071/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417071/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","National Parks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government when they plan to announce their decision on the revision of National Park boundaries.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417072","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","Sexual violence in Burma remains a significant problem. Our work to date has included funding for an international non-governmental organisation to provide training to various local non-state actors on the protection of women in armed conflict and supporting a project that creates legal aid centres and provides training to paralegals to help provide advice and assistance on documenting crimes of sexual violence. Our work to provide educational courses to the Burmese military has also included components on sexual violence in conflict. The lack of effective documentation means that many cases go unreported and unpunished. During his visit in July, the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for East Devon (Mr Swire), launched the International Protocol on the Documentation and Investigation of Sexual Violence at an event in Rangoon attended by Burmese civil society groups. The International Protocol provides the know-how to enable governments and civil society organisations to produce effective reporting to an evidentiary standard capable of supporting prosecutions.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:20:28.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417072/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417072/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Burma: Sexual Offences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what funding they provide to organisations that support women in Burma to ensure the proper documentation of sexual violence resulting from conflict in that country.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL1992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417073","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-21","<p>By the end of the Connecting Devon and Somerset Phase 1 project (December 2016) over 277,000 additional homes and businesses will have access to superfast broadband. As of 30 June 2015, 121,343 premises had gained access to superfast broadband due to this public investment.</p><p> </p><p>Connecting Devon and Somerset have signed a contract with Airband under their Phase 2 contract to extend superfast coverage to an additional 4,794 premises across Exmoor and Dartmoor. Roll-out to these premises will start in February 2016 and is to be completed by November 2016. Assuming completion of the announced commercial coverage, a further 106,725 premises in Devon and Somerset would remain without superfast coverage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The economic impact of superfast broadband coverage is assessed in the study published by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport in November 2013 at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-broadband-impact-study--2</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-21T15:14:21.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417073/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417073/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","Broadband: South West","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 30 July (HL1682), what assessment they have made of the rate of progress in improving superfast broadband provision in Devon and Somerset; and what is their assessment of the impact of that progress on regional economic performance.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417074","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>We believe there is no case for a Chief Inspector of Charities.</p><p> </p><p>As the independent regulator, the Charity Commission for England and Wales and can intervene where there is serious misconduct or mismanagement or risk to charity property. We are currently strengthening the regulatorâs powers to intervene in the Charities (Protection and Social Investments) Bill.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-09-21T15:34:54.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417074/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417074/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Charities: Inspections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their assessment of the case for establishing a new office of Chief Inspector of Charities in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417075","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p /> <p>No decisions have been taken relating to the number and locations of magistratesâ courts and all responses to the ongoing consultation on the court estate will be carefully considered before any decisions are made.</p><p> </p><p>Our programme of courts reform will create a more modern and efficient service which works better for victims and witnesses. Witnesses could particularly benefit from such arrangements as we seek to expand existing provision such as video links meaning witnesses do not have to attend court in person increasing their privacy and reducing risk.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-09-21T14:41:48.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417075/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417075/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-07","Magistrates' Courts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their assessment of whether the present changes to the number and locations of magistrate courts meet the interests of witnesses, in particular regarding their privacy and protection.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417076","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","We are confident of UK sovereignty over British Gibraltar Territorial Waters (BGTW) under international law and have made our position clear to the Spanish government.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:20:14.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417076/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417076/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their assessment of recent statements by the Spanish Minister for Europe in relation to British waters surrounding Gibraltar that Spain does not recognise United Kingdom rights over maritime areas not covered by Article X of the Treaty of Utrecht 1713.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417077","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is operationally independent from Government and carries out its functions within the framework of statutory objectives and duties agreed by Parliament. This includes requirements to publicly consult and perform cost benefit analysis on their relevant rules and policies. These questions are therefore a matter for the FCA as an independent regulator.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Noble Lord by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL1998 ; HL1999","2015-09-21T15:31:34.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417077/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417077/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Banks: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is the estimated cost to the British economy of the Financial Conduct Authorityâs policies on the banking sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL1997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417078","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is operationally independent from Government and carries out its functions within the framework of statutory objectives and duties agreed by Parliament. This includes requirements to publicly consult and perform cost benefit analysis on their relevant rules and policies. These questions are therefore a matter for the FCA as an independent regulator.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Noble Lord by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL1997 ; HL1999","2015-09-21T15:31:34.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417078/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Banks: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the Financial Conduct Authorityâs regulation of the banking sector, and of the impact of its regulation on banksâ ability to respond to the needs of customers.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL1998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417079","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is operationally independent from Government and carries out its functions within the framework of statutory objectives and duties agreed by Parliament. This includes requirements to publicly consult and perform cost benefit analysis on their relevant rules and policies. These questions are therefore a matter for the FCA as an independent regulator.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Noble Lord by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL1997 ; HL1998","2015-09-21T15:31:34.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417079/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417079/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Banks: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what changes the Financial Conduct Authority has implemented regarding the setting up of bank accounts for customers in the United Kingdom over the past year; and what assessment they have made of the impact of such changes on the time it takes to set up a bank account in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL1999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417080","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government has been funding Bikeability cycle training in schools since 2006/07. The Department for Transport funds training in England and Transport for London funds training in London.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Bikeability training is delivered to children between school years 5-9 (ages 9-14). Bikeability training consists of three levels. Level 1 and Level 2 training is aimed at children aged 9-11 years old and Level 3 training is aimed at children aged 11-14 years old.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Delivery statistics are not collated by age group. However, data on the number of training places delivered for each level of Bikeability training is available from 2012/13 to 2013/14. We have used these data to give an indication of the number of children trained in cycling proficiency at school in each local authority area in England (excluding London) for the age ranges 9-11 years and 11-14 years. Please see the attached tables 1 and 2. The figures are based on information provided by Local Highway Authorities (LHA) and School Games Organiser Host Schools (SGOHS).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-17T11:15:01.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417080/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417080/answer","HL2000 - Bikeability training.docx","HL2000 - Tables for Bikeability Training","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417080/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-07","Children: Cycling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many children aged (1) 8â11, and (2) 11â14, were trained in cycling proficiency at school in each local authority area in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL2000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417081","Wales Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>We will set out a timetable for decisions on the future of the Severn Tolls shortly. In taking this forward we will ensure we consult fully with key interested parties, including the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-09-15T11:18:36.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417081/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417081/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-09-07","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what discussions they have had with ministers of the Welsh Government about the future of the charging of tolls on the Severn Bridge.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417082","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>As the Prime Minister stated on 24th June 2015, this Government is committed to the electrification of Great Western line from Swansea to Cardiff and on to London.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Transport announced on the 25th June 2015 that Great Western was a top priority for delivery andãthat is why he has asked Sir Peter Hendy, the new chair of Network Rail, to put forward proposals for replanning the enhancement programme across England and Wales, which includes electrification.ã Sir Peter is due to report to the Secretary of State in the Autumn.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-16T13:28:43.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417082/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417082/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-07","South Wales Railway Line: Electrification","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether there has been any revision to the target date for the completion of the electrification of the South Wales Main Line railway link between London and Swansea.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417083","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The banking tax roadmap set out at the Summer Budget means that banks will end up paying a corporation tax rate which is the lowest in the G7 and lower than at any time under the last Labour government. There is also an allowance in the surcharge for the first Â£25 million of a banking groupâs profits, reducing the impact on smaller banks and excluding many altogether.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to improving competition in banking to improve outcomes for consumers. Challenger banks play a crucial role in providing consumers with more choice on the high street.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has already taken significant action to improve competition in banking and create an environment that reduces barriers to entry and incentivises new banks to enter the market. This includes:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p>driving the delivery and supporting the continued success of the Current Account Switch Service and Midata, so customers can compare personal current accounts and switch banks where they see a better deal â simply, quickly and reliably;</p></li><li><p>committing at Budget 2015 to deliver an open standard to Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) in UK banking â as well as helping customers engage more with their bank, it will drive innovation and increase competitive intensity by supporting the growth of technology that can be used by banks and non-bank providers to offer new products;</p></li><li><p>improving competition in the small and medium sized enterprise (SME) lending market by requiring the major banks to share SME credit data with other lenders through designated credit reference agencies, and to offer any SMEs they turn down for finance the chance to have their details passed to online platforms that can help match them with alternative finance providers;</p></li><li><p>announcing at Summer Budget 2015 that the Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) and Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) will establish a joint New Bank Unit to help prospective new banks enter the market and through the early days of authorisation â the PRA and FCA will also produce annual reports on how they are delivering against their respective competition objectives;</p></li><li><p>putting competition at the heart of the regulatory system by creating the new Payments System Regulator to ensure challenger banks can access payment systems on fair and equal terms â the Government has also created a single, stronger competition regulator: the Competition and Markets Authority.</p></li></ul><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-09-21T15:32:08.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417083/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417083/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Banks: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they are taking to help small lenders to compete effectively with the larger banks, in the light of the new bank corporation tax surcharge.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417084","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>Since the growth voucher programme launched in January 2014, we have carried out two qualitative assessments and published the findings. Our evaluation is ongoing. All research and evaluation relating to the programme will be published and can be found at the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-16T15:56:32.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417084/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417084/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Small Businesses: Advisory Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of the Growth Vouchers programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417085","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-25","<p>The Government is already undertaking steps to raise awareness of government projects designed to help small businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For those firms looking to export, UK Trade and Investment provides tailored advice, information and support to small businesses, whether exporting for the first time or more experienced exporters seeking to expand their business into new but challenging markets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>UKTI runs events for small businesses in towns and cities across the country, providing access to support and information locally and discussions with trade advisers. It also works with partner organisations such as the Business Growth Service, Growth Hubs, the major banks, and chambers of commerce to help small businesses export. UKTI delivers thousands of international business opportunities for companies to access online and also runs online exporting webinars with 15,000 companies expected to attend 500+ events this year. Support is also made available through <a href="http://gov.uk/ukti" target="_blank">gov.uk/ukti</a> and across UKTI social media channels.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Building on this the Government is launching Exporting is GREAT (part of the award-winning GREAT campaign) during Export Week in November 2015. The Governmentâs most ambitious export campaign ever, it aims to inspire and support 100,000 new British businesses to sell their goods and services overseas by 2020. Export Week itself will see over 90 events across the UK, attracting over 5000 companies to attend exporting related activities in a single week<br> <br></p><p> </p><p>For advice on hiring apprentices, the Government works with the Skills Funding Agency to encourage businesses of all sizes to recruit apprentices and trainees through its free online vacancy filling system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The offer includes the Apprenticeship Grant for Employers, which provides a Â£1,500 grant for employers with less than 50 staff for each of their first five apprentices aged 16-24, supporting small businesses who want to recruit apprentices in this age group. By joining forces with HMRC more than 90,000 businesses of all sizes are made aware of our apprenticeships offer every month.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We also work with the Federation of Small Businesses and the British Chambers of Commerce to encourage more small businesses to embrace apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For other general business support, we have established a network of regional Growth Hubs which offer support and advice at the local level, as well as the online Business Growth Service, designed to help high growth companies reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-25T12:29:55.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417085/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417085/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they plan to take to raise awareness of government projects designed to help small businesses.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417086","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK has played a key role in the negotiation of the Sustainable Development Goals and fully supports the Open Working Group proposal which will be formally agreed at the UN summit later this month. DFID runs a range of programmes to support entrepreneurs, including working with business action groups, providing support to improve the investment climate for small businesses and hosting challenge funds to which entrepreneurs can apply to for grants.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-09-18T12:02:03.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417086/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417086/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-07","Developing Countries: New Businesses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they plan to take, if any, to support the campaign launched by Dell for the post-2015 UN development agenda to promote sustainable development through entrepreneurship.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417087","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-22","<p>We encourage business support across the country by investing in projects in many regions. The Government is investing Â£15m in 4 University Enterprise Zones (UEZs) to test how university-led incubators, with associated business support, can contribute to economic growth and productivity gains. The pilot UEZs are in Bradford (Leeds City Region), Bristol, Liverpool and Nottingham. The Government is also investing Â£4.8m capital to support the development of a new spin-out centre for small high tech businesses in the life sciences sector, based at Cambridge Science Park.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-22T13:11:53.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417087/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417087/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","New Businesses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they are taking to encourage more accelerators and incubators outside London to support all entrepreneurs across the country.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417088","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>In his statement to Parliament on 7 September the Prime Minister stated that, in full accordance with internationally agreed rules, the UK will ensure that the full cost of supporting thousands of Syrian refugees in the UK will be met through our aid spending for the first year.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-09-18T12:09:06.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417088/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417088/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-07","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether new spending on migrants will count towards the statutory target of spending 0.7 per cent of gross national income on overseas aid.","false","Biography information for Lord Lipsey",,"Lord Lipsey","HL2008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417089","Department for Education","false","2015-09-16","<p>The governmentâs plan for education is designed to help every student, regardless of their background, develop the knowledge, skills and values to prepare them for life in modern Britain. That is why we are reforming GCSEs and A levels to be robust and rigorous, to match the best education systems in the world and to keep pace with universitiesâ and employersâ demands.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have also introduced gold-standard technical and vocational qualifications, ensuring our young people can choose from a wide range of academic and vocational courses.</p><p>The government has consulted extensively with a range of educational stakeholders including the teaching sectors and employers.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-09-16T14:31:17.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417089/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417089/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","GCSE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their assessment of the criticisms of GCSEs by the High Master of St Paulâs School who was reported in the press on 18 August as saying that "one size doesnât fit all" and that "the curse of GCSE is that the size on offer fits no one".","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL2009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417090","Home Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The largest volumes of calls in the Home Office are handled by HM Passport Office and UK Visas and Immigration. The Home Office does not publish centrally collated figures for call handling.</p><p>HM Passport Office calls are either handled directly through its commercial partner Teleperformance or at one of the in-house call centres in Liverpool and Southport. Both Teleperformance and the in-house call centres aim to answer 80% of calls in 30 seconds.</p><p>UK Visas and Immigration calls are handled either directly at the in-house call centres in Croydon and Sheffield, or through one of two commercial partners, HGS and Sitel. UKVI in-house Contact Centres aim to answer the majority of calls in three minutes.</p><p>All commercial partner and in-house staff undergo an assessed foundation training course; which includes modules around required knowledge, communication, effective questioning and call control.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-21T15:48:57.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417090/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417090/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Home Office: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the Home Office has target times by which members of the public can reasonably expect to get through on the telephone and speak to an official; by what percentage extent there has been a change over the past three years in the number of telephone calls from the public seeking information or assistance from the Home Office; and what training in communication skills is provided for the officials in that Department.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL2010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417091","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p /> <p>Since April 2015 the average answer time for calls to the Public Enquiry Line has been 28 seconds. The Ministry of Justice does not have set target times for call answering.</p><p> </p><p>Calls to the MoJ public enquiry line have decreased steadily since 2012. Volumes reduced by 40% between 2012 and 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Regular training is held for staff for on call handling and customer service.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-09-21T14:44:17.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417091/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417091/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-07","Ministry of Justice: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the Ministry of Justice has target times by which members of the public can reasonably expect to get through on the telephone and speak to an official; by what percentage extent there has been a change over the past three years in the number of telephone calls from the public seeking information or assistance from the Ministry of Justice; and what training in communication skills is provided for the officials in that Department.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL2011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417092","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-14","<p /> <p>The current targets across DWP for answering telephone calls from the public are:</p><p> </p><p>Â· Working Age Benefits - 2 minutes (with the exception of Universal Credit which is 1 minute 30 seconds).</p><p>Â· State Pension, State Pension Credit, Personal Independence Payment, Disability Living Allowance, Attendance Allowance, Carers Allowance - 1 minute 30 seconds.</p><p>Â· Child Maintenance Group - 1 minute.</p><p> </p><p>We are unable to provide information relating to the request for a percentage change over the past three years in the number of telephone calls from the public, as prior to April 2013, reporting was produced through the telephony platform itself. As the platform has a 14 rolling month data retention policy, and no robust archive of data was maintained at this time, robust data is not available for this period.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>All staff working in the Department for Work and Pensions who are new to delivering phone services receive job specific training which includes communication skills. New members of staff also have the opportunity to observe experienced staff allowing them to pick up a range of communication skills from experienced Agents.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-09-14T14:10:11.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417092/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417092/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-07","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the Department for Work and Pensions has target times by which members of the public can reasonably expect to get through on the telephone and speak to an official; by what percentage extent there has been a change over the past three years in the number of telephone calls from the public seeking information or assistance from the Department for Work and Pensions; and what training in communication skills is provided for the officials in that Department.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL2012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417093","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Departmentâs target is for 93% of telephone enquiries to be answered within 45 seconds.</p><p> </p><p>Call volumes to the general enquiries telephone line for the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills were as follows:</p><p>April 2012-March 2013: 41,562 calls</p><p>April 2013-March 2014: 31,426 calls (a 24% decrease from 2012-2013)</p><p>April 2014-March 2015: 30,533 calls (a 3% decrease from 2013-2014)</p><p> </p><p>Training provision on communication skills is dependent on the needs of officials and teams. An advanced level course on the professional handling of telephone calls was most recently delivered to frontline call handlers on Thursday 20 August.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-11T13:14:49.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417093/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417093/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has target times by which members of the public can reasonably expect to get through on the telephone and speak to an official; by what percentage extent there has been a change over the past three years in the number of telephone calls from the public seeking information or assistance from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills; and what training in communication skills is provided for the officials in that Department.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL2013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417094","HM Treasury","true","2015-09-21","<p>As stated in an earlier response (HL897), HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) publishes its performance data quarterly on the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC handles 50 million calls a year from customers. It aims to answer 80 per cent of all calls and accepts that it is not currently delivering on that aspiration. HMRC published a press release on 25 June in which it apologised for the poor service, acknowledged that some customers were struggling to get through on the telephone and outlined a number of initiatives it is putting in place to improve performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-09-21T15:54:07.557Z","2015-09-22T14:57:41.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417094/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417094/answer",,"Lord Bridges","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417094/answer/previousversion/22479",,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord OâNeill of Gatley on 30 July (HL1654), whether HM Revenue and Customs has target times by which members of the public can reasonably expect to get through on the telephone and speak to an official; and by what percentage extent there has been a change over the past three years in the number of telephone calls from the public seeking information or assistance from that Department.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL2014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417095","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government of Yemen and Saudi-led Coalition have made military gains in recent weeks against the Houthis and forces loyal to former president Saleh. We hope this will help build a base for the future return of the legitimate Yemeni government. A political solution is the best way to achieve long-term stability in Yemen, and we remain fully supportive of the UNâs efforts to achieve a lasting ceasefire and resumption of an inclusive political process. The humanitarian situation remains dire, with eighty per cent of the population in need of assistance. The Department for International Development has allocated Â£55 million, through UN agencies and humanitarian non-governmental organisations, to support Yemenis affected by the crisis. We remain extremely concerned by reports of alleged violations of international humanitarian and human rights law, and continue to raise the importance of compliance with all parties to the conflict. The risk of terrorist groups, such as al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula and the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) in Yemen, exploiting the instability is also a major concern. We continue to work with regional and international partners to tackle the threat.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:19:46.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417095/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417095/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Yemen: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their current assessment of the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417096","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>According to the UN, 21 million people - more than 80% of the population - are in need of humanitarian assistance in Yemen. Of those, over 6 million people are facing severe food shortages, with households struggling to meet their daily needs. In particular, 1.8 million children are most at risk and require access to life-saving nutrition services. In Hodeidah city alone, UNICEF have warned that 96,000 severely malnourished children are at risk of dying.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK is one of the largest donors to the crisis in Yemen and has announced Â£55 million to respond to the humanitarian crisis in Yemen, focused on the most urgent life-saving needs. UK aid will provide emergency shelter, healthcare, water, food and nutrition assistance for at least half a million Yemenis, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the international humanitarian response.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-09-18T12:00:33.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417096/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417096/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-07","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the humanitarian needs of the people of Yemen; and what humanitarian assistance is being provided to them.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417097","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>According to Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar figures, the maximum delay to vehicle traffic crossing the Gibraltar-Spain border in 2015 were: 90 minutes for June; 105 minutes for July; and 105 minutes for August. In 2014 the figures were 320 minutes for June; 180 minutes for July and 300 minutes for August. While we have started to see an overall downward trend, disproportionate delays remain unacceptable. Working with Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar, we provide regular updates to the European Commission on the flow of traffic at the border. We continue to press the Spanish government to implement the European Commissionâs recommendations quickly, in full and in consultation with Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar. The Commission has welcomed the steps taken by Gibraltar in response to their recommendations.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL2018","2015-09-18T12:10:14.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417097/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417097/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their assessment of the delays to cars and freight vehicles crossing the border between Gibraltar and Spain in June, July and August 2015; and how this compares with those months in 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>According to Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar figures, the maximum delay to vehicle traffic crossing the Gibraltar-Spain border in 2015 were: 90 minutes for June; 105 minutes for July; and 105 minutes for August. In 2014 the figures were 320 minutes for June; 180 minutes for July and 300 minutes for August. While we have started to see an overall downward trend, disproportionate delays remain unacceptable. Working with Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar, we provide regular updates to the European Commission on the flow of traffic at the border. We continue to press the Spanish government to implement the European Commissionâs recommendations quickly, in full and in consultation with Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar. The Commission has welcomed the steps taken by Gibraltar in response to their recommendations.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL2017","2015-09-18T12:10:14.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417098/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether all the recommendations of the European Commission to facilitate movement across the Gibraltar to Spain border have been implemented by the United Kingdom and the Spanish government.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Recent illegal incursions by Spanish Customs vessels into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters (BGTW) are unacceptable and unlawful under international law. Incursions are a violation of sovereignty, not a threat to it. They do not weaken or undermine the legal basis in international law for British sovereignty over Gibraltar, including BGTW.</p><p>In response to the incursion on 22 August we protested to the Spanish government at a high level and secured their assurances that they will respect the importance of safety at sea. Working closely with Her Majesty's Government of Gibraltar, we have agreed with Spain to step up law enforcement cooperation in the fight against organised crime.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:19:41.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417099/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their assessment of recent incidents involving Spanish customs boats entering British Territorial waters around Gibraltar, and what action has since been taken.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>In June, July and August 2015, there were 45, 40 and 41 unlawful incursions respectively by Spanish State vessels into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters. For the same months in 2014, the numbers were 46, 31 and 25.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:18:42.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417100/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many incursions there were into British Territorial waters around Gibraltar by the Spanish Guardia Civil, customs officers and navy in June, July, and August 2015; and how this compares with those months in 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417101","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Chief Secretary to the Treasury regularly advises the Northern Ireland Minister for Finance and Personnel of the Northern Ireland Executiveâs current control totals through correspondence, including any changes which need to be incorporated through the course of the year following fiscal events and Estimates rounds. There are also regular discussions between officials. There is no formal requirement for the letters to be acknowledged by Northern Ireland Ministers.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-09-21T15:11:11.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417101/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417101/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they have advised the Northern Ireland Executive of the control totals available to it for financial year 2015â16; if so, when that advice was communicated to the Northern Ireland Executive; and what response was received.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417102","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer (HL839) that I gave to him on 7 July 2015 with regard to the Northern Ireland Executiveâs control totals for 2015-16. Details regarding the budget passed by the Northern Ireland Assembly are published by the Department of Finance and Personnel in Northern Ireland, and by the Assembly itself.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-09-21T15:32:56.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417102/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417102/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs GovernmentÂ what is the financial difference between the control totals for the Northern Ireland Executive for financial year 2015â16 and the budget passed by the Northern Ireland Assembly in July 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417103","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer (HL321) that I gave to him on 8 June 2015.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-09-21T15:31:01.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417103/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417103/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they plan to allow the Northern Ireland Executive to spend in excess of its control totals for financial year 2015â16.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417104","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>Under the Stormont House Agreement the Government will provide the Northern Ireland Executive with flexibility to use Reinvestment and Reform Initiative capital borrowing powers to fund a Northern Ireland public sector voluntary exit scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-09-15T11:18:14.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417104/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417104/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-09-07","Northern Ireland Civil Service: Redundancy Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is the source of funds being made available to the Northern Ireland Executive to allow it to finance the voluntary exit scheme for Northern Ireland Civil Servants.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417105","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>I refer the Noble Lord to the Secretary of State for Northern Irelandâs remarks to the House of Commons on 8 September 2015 which set out the Governmentâs and the Chief Constableâs current assessment of the Provisional IRA (PIRA).</p><p>We have no plans to remove PIRA from the list of proscribed organisations.</p><p>The Government has made clear that there is no place for any paramilitary group in a democratic society. Issues arising out of continued paramilitary activity and remaining structures need to be urgently addressed in cross-party talks, and that is our priority.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop","HL2026","2015-09-21T14:43:39.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417105/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417105/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-09-07","IRA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the status, structure and operational capability of the Provisional IRA.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417106","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>I refer the Noble Lord to the Secretary of State for Northern Irelandâs remarks to the House of Commons on 8 September 2015 which set out the Governmentâs and the Chief Constableâs current assessment of the Provisional IRA (PIRA).</p><p>We have no plans to remove PIRA from the list of proscribed organisations.</p><p>The Government has made clear that there is no place for any paramilitary group in a democratic society. Issues arising out of continued paramilitary activity and remaining structures need to be urgently addressed in cross-party talks, and that is our priority.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop","HL2025","2015-09-21T14:43:38.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417106/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417106/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-09-07","IRA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they plan to remove the Provisional IRA from the list of proscribed organisations.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417107","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Home Office estimate that there were 713 visas issued to nurses in 2011/12 to whom the pay threshold and six year cap would apply if they are still resident in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England (HEE) is responsible for delivering a better health and healthcare workforce for England and for ensuring a secure future supply of nurses with the right skills, values and behaviours to meet future demand.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HEE has increased nurse training places by 11% over the last two years and there are currently over 20,000 more professionally qualified clinical staff since 2010, including over 8,100 more nurses on our wards.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-16T13:30:35.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417107/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Nurses: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many NHS nurses they estimate will be affected by the new pay threshold for migrants; and whether they anticipate there will be a shortfall in NHS nursing staff as a result.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL2027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417108","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Department has not set any targets for the recruitment of British nurses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>National Health Service organisations are best placed to decide how many staff they employ. Services should be tailored to meet the needs of their patients and local communities, to deliver safe care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS trusts are able to recruit nurses using the NHS Jobs dedicated online recruitment service for the NHS, free of charge.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-16T13:43:57.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417108/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Nurses: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether there are targets for the recruitment of British nurses; if so, what they are; and how much it is estimated that this recruitment process will cost.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL2028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417109","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>An inclusive political transition in Syria is the only way to end the conflict and to alleviate Syriaâs humanitarian crisis. The UK continues to call on the Syrian regime and its supporters to engage seriously in the political process. Violence in Syria, particularly on the part of the Assad governmentâs deliberate targeting of civilians, is the root cause of the current refugee crisis. Over four million Syrians have had to flee their homes and a quarter of a million Syrians have been killed. The UK will continue to work with the UN Special Envoy, Staffan de Mistura, and our international partners to press for a political settlement to resolve the conflict in Syria in line with the Geneva CommuniquÃ©.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:18:29.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417109/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417109/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Syria: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what strategy they have to help to end the conflict in Syria in view of the current migrant crisis in Europe.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL2029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417110","Home Office","false","2015-09-22","<p>An expansion to the Syrian Vulnerable Persons' Scheme has been announced. Her Majesty's Government now intends to resettle 20,000 Syrians in need of protection during this Parliament.</p><p>The Scheme is based on need, prioritising those who cannot be supported effectively in their region of origin: women and children at risk, people in severe need of medical care and survivors of torture and violence. We work closely with the UNHCR to identify cases that they deem to be in need of resettlement and we will continue this work to ensure even greater numbers are identified and provided with refuge in the UK. Individuals admitted under the Scheme to date are in addition to nearly 5,000 Syrian nationals who have been granted asylum in the UK since the crisis there began.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-22T14:55:54.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417110/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417110/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Asylum: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government (1) whether the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme will be expanded and (2) why so few vulnerable Syrians have been relocated to date.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL2030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417111","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The findings of the Muslim Brotherhood Review have been considered by Whitehall Departments in a process led by the National Security Adviser. It has illustrated some of the challenges posed by those whose views may be seen to contribute towards creating the space for more extreme views to flourish. The Government is continuing to develop our broader policy response on this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The costs of the review were absorbed in routine administrative spend with the exception of Sir John Jenkinsâ travel which amounted to Â£8791.79. The Government sought to save travel costs as far as possible through working through our network of Embassies and High Commissions; packaging regional travel to avoid more expensive fares from London; and hosting international partners in London.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-09-21T15:34:06.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417111/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417111/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Muslim Brotherhood Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government (1) how the Government-sponsored review of the Muslim Brotherhood, led by Sir John Jenkins, has informed Government policy towards the Muslim Brotherhood; and (2) how much the review cost.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL2031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417112","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>We have regular discussions with the Governments of Saudi Arabia, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates about various issues including the Muslim Brotherhood Review. We expect the main findings of the Review to be made public in the context of the Extremism Strategy. We will keep Parliament updated on developments.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-18T13:18:09.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417112/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417112/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-07","Muslim Brotherhood Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what discussion they have had with (1) Saudi Arabia, (2) Egypt, and (3) the United Arab Emirates, following the delivery of the Government-sponsored review of the Muslim Brotherhood in March.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL2032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417113","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>In 2014-15 there were 145 cases of children under the age of 18 being detained in police cells after being sectioned under the Mental Health Act 1983; this represents a 40% decrease from the previous year, and a 55% decrease since the figures began to be collected in 2011-12.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Crisis Care Concordat was launched in February 2014 seeking to improve the experience of those in crisis, and in particular, prevent those detained under section 136 of the Mental Health Act being held in police cells. All localities signed up to the principles of the Concordat before the end of 2014. Detailed action plans are now in place across England setting out how local partners will work together to improve service responses for people in crisis. The Department of Health, NHS England and Mind continue to work with local areas to strengthen and improve their âlocal Concordat action plansâ.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As announced by the Home Secretary in May earlier this year, this Government will also be reforming the law on the use of police cells to end this practice altogether for under 18s. This will be backed by Â£15 million to improve the provision of health-based places of safety so that there is better availability of alternatives to police cells for people of all ages.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-16T13:45:31.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417113/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417113/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many children aged under 18 were detained in police custody during the past 12 months, after being sectioned under the Mental Health Act 1983; and what action they plan to take, if any, to prevent such detention in future.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417114","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The last prevalence survey, published in 2004, found that around 10% of children were suffering from a diagnosable medical condition. Around one in a thousand children was a child aged under 10 suffering from severe depression. Based on these figures, the charity Young Minds has estimated that around 8,000 children aged under 10 suffer from severe depression.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to improving children and young peopleâs mental health and wellbeing as a major priority. All clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have been asked to work with their local partners to develop plans to transform their offer through the development of local transformation plans. These plans, alongside existing investment, should include the full spectrum of interventions: from prevention and resilience building, to support and care for existing and emerging mental health problems, as well as transitions between services and addressing the needs of the most vulnerable. This local transformation will be supported by a national programme of work, which includes piloting single points of contact so that young people have access to mental health advice and support in schools and the extension and expansion of the Children and Young People's Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Department is commissioning a new comprehensive prevalence survey of children and young peopleâs mental health. The programme is on track to announce a contractor in autumn 2015, and final publication is expected in 2018. The findings of the survey will help identify where best to target improvements.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-16T13:48:56.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417114/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417114/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Mental Illness: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment has been made of the mental health problems being experienced by children in the United Kingdom; and what action they plan to take, if any, to reduce the number of children aged under 10 who suffer from severe depression.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417115","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The wellbeing of the young people previously supported by Kids Company continues to be our top priority. Since the closure, Local Authorities have been reviewing the cases handed to them by Kids Company to determine the support services the young people require. Funding is being made available to local authorities to support the transition of Kids Company young people to other services.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-09-21T15:33:28.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417115/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417115/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Kids Company","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of what has happened to the children previously cared for by Kids Company.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417116","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-15","<p>Since 2010 the Government has invested over Â£500 million to help local authorities and the voluntary sector prevent and tackle homelessness, enabling local authorities prevent over 935,000 households from becoming homeless.</p><p>The Government wants to help hard working families achieve their dream of home ownership. But not all tenants of housing associations are able to benefit from the discounts the last Government introduced. Thatâs why this Government want to give housing association tenants the same home ownership opportunities as council tenants. Each housing association home sold under the Right to Buy extension will be replaced.</p><p>Local authorities should use resources effectively and efficiently and those with a Housing Revenue Account will be required to sell vacant high value housing in order to help fund the building of more affordable homes and the extension of Right to Buy to housing association tenants.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-09-15T11:20:50.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417116/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417116/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Social Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the implications for meeting the housing needs of homeless people and those living in overcrowded conditions of social housing stock being sold off.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417117","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Government has no annual housing target but is taking action through a wide range of programmes to boost housing supply and to increase home ownership.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-09-15T11:21:09.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417117/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417117/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what are the constraints preventing the achievement of the 200,000 annual housebuilding target.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417118","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>BIS constantly review occupancy costs through effective data management utilising best in class market advisors to provide current market rental evidence. London particularly has seen an increase in office rental values driven in part by the demand for alternative residential use. BIS have adopted strategies to mitigate the costs resulting in a cost per person and space utilisation being lower in London than regions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A BIS 2020 Estate strategy is currently being developed to maximise the efficient use of office space across the office portfolio. The new estates strategy will drive significant reductions in floor space and coupled with greater emphasis on online working will deliver substantial savings over the spending review period.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-11T13:16:02.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417118/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417118/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Offices: Rents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the costs of renting office space in cities, especially London, and of the effect on those costs as more previously disused office space is converted into new flats.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417119","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government published its assessment of the impacts of the spirits duty change in the Tax Information and Impact Notes published alongside the Budget document. Copies of Budget related documentation are available in the Printed Paper Office.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-09-21T15:11:33.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417119/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417119/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Spirits: Excise Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is the Health Impact Assessment of the two per cent cut in spirits duty announced in the March 2015 Budget.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417120","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-16","<p>Our aim is to publish the 25 year Food and Farming Plan around the end of the year. The plan will have a strong focus on the potential for our world leading food and farming sector, including the alcoholic drinks industry, to create jobs and deliver economic growth. The issue of alcohol related harm is complex and multi-faceted, and we have regular discussions with Public Health England and the Department of Health on this and other areas of common interest.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-16T12:47:16.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417120/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417120/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Food","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government when they plan to publish a 25-year plan to boost productivity and growth in the food and drink sectors; and whether this will include consideration of any negative consequences of increased alcohol production.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417121","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-15","<p>We have regular meetings with the Department of Health and Public Health England to discuss issues of common interest, including our plans to support productivity and growth in the food and drink sectors.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-15T12:20:52.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417121/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417121/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Food","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they have sought advice from bodies such as Public Health England on their plans to support productivity and growth in the food and drink sectors.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417122","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-15","<p>There is no conflict between plans to support growth and productivity in the food and drink industry with other Government priorities relating to obesity and alcohol related harm. We want to expand UK food and drink production so that we can displace imports and increase our exports. We aim to see more consumers benefit from access to our world-beating, high quality and nutritious food.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-15T14:09:39.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417122/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417122/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Food","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether plans to support productivity and growth in the food and drink sectors are in conflict with other Government priorities to reduce obesity and alcohol-related harm.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417123","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Guidelines Development Group, a group of independent experts, has been tasked with developing lower-risk drinking guidelines for the United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers to consider. The Group is currently researching and developing a proposal on the guidelines, including a UK-wide approach for guidance on alcohol and pregnancy. We are expecting to consult on these later in the year.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-17T11:20:43.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417123/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417123/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-07","Alcoholic Drinks: Consumption","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government when they propose to publish any updated guidelines on safe drinking limits, following a review by the Chief Medical Officer.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417124","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-10","<p>Over 170 former local staff have already been relocated to the UK under the Ex Gratia Redundancy Scheme along with approximately 400 family members. Over 35 more local staff have had their application approved and been granted a visa, along with their immediate family members and will be relocating to the UK in the near future.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-09-10T16:45:22.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417124/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417124/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Afghanistan: Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many Afghan interpreters (1) have already been relocated to the United Kingdom under the post-conflict redundancy scheme, and (2) have had their application approved and are awaiting relocation.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL2044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417125","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-11","<p>Under Her Majesty's Government's Intimidation Policy for locally employed staff in Afghanistan staff can raise a claim of intimidation and following investigation we provide them with the most appropriate measure to mitigate any risk they may face. This can include security advice, financial support to move location within Afghanistan or relocation to the UK. Under the current policy no local staff have been relocated to the UK, and we have relocated some 30 local staff within Afghanistan.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-09-11T13:31:24.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417125/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417125/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Afghanistan: Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many Afghan interpreters (1) have applied for, and (2) been granted, relocation to the United Kingdom under the policy regarding intimidation.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL2045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417126","Home Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>To date 17 local authorities have received relocated Afghans under the Afghan Locally Engaged Civilian Ex Gratia Scheme. It would not be appropriate for us to release details of where individuals are currently being placed or where they may be placed in the future, as this may undermine their privacy.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-21T15:41:52.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417126/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417126/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-07","Afghanistan: Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government which United Kingdom authorities are participating in the scheme to receive relocated Afghan interpreters.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL2046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417127","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Department for Transportâs officials have held a meeting on 7 September 2015 with the Committee on Toxicology and Public Health England to discuss these concerns. All sides agreed constructive steps to ensure the Committeeâs concerns are addressed. The Government plans to write to members of both Houses who have received correspondence or responses to Parliamentary Questions on the issue, with a full description of the Committeeâs advice in the light of these discussions with the Committee on Toxicology. A copy of this letter will be placed in the libraries of both Houses of Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-16T13:51:03.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417127/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417127/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-07","Toxicity of Chemicals in Food Consumer Products and the Environment Committee","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, in the light of Item 3 of the minutes of the meeting of the Committee on Toxicity of Chemicals in Food and the Environment (COT) held on 30 June, relating to inaccurate representation of the Committeeâs conclusions in official replies, what steps they plan to take to address the fact that COT believes "COT advice to Government ha[s] been repeatedly misrepresented in ministerial communications, including answers to Parliamentary questions"; and whether they plan to inform members of both Houses who receive those answers about their correspondence with COT on this issue.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417128","Attorney General","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) has participated in carbon offsetting resulting from air travel. However, it has not kept central records of expenditure in respect of carbon offsetting in the last three years and to provide this information would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Government Legal Department has spent Â£171.28 on carbon offsetting over the last 3 financial years. In 2012-13, Â£42.13 was paid South Pole Holding AG and in 2013-14 Â£129.15 was paid to Carbon Footprint Ltd. The companies paid were those who won the e-auctions to provide Certified Emissions Reductions (CERs) held by Crown Commercial Services in each of the years identified.</p><p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) has spent Â£153 towards carbon offsetting over the last three years through Crown Commercial Services carbon offsetting arrangements. In 2013, Â£79 was paid for Fujian Wind power for 116 CERS (Certified Emission Reductions) and Â£74 to EDF for 104 CERS in January 2014.</p><p>The Attorney Generalâs Office and HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate have not incurred any expenditure on carbon offsetting over the past three years.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-09-14T16:30:45.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417128/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417128/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-09-07","Attorney General: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much the Law Officers' Departments spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417129","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-10","<p /> <p>The number of offenders sentenced at all courts, by type of sentence and custodial sentence length band, for the offence of encouraging or assisting suicide or attempted suicide, in England and Wales, for the period 2009 to 2014, is available at the following link:</p><p><em> </em></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428943/cjs-outcomes-by-offence-data-tool.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428943/cjs-outcomes-by-offence-data-tool.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>Select the offence â76 Aiding Suicideâ to present information on offenders sentenced at all courts for this offence.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice does not publish the average custodial sentence length in circumstances where the number of offenders sentenced to immediate custody is too small to give a meaningful average â specifically when there are fewer than five offenders.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-10T13:55:23.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417129/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417129/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-07","Euthanasia: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average sentence for the offence of assisted suicide is for each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","9328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417130","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>There are four pieces of work where McKinsey have been providing assistance to the Department:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>operating costs across the Department and Partner Organisations;</li><li>the cost of goods and services procured from third parties, led by the Crown Commercial Service;</li><li>a review of the Student Loans Company; and</li><li>cost drivers in Further Education, jointly with the Department for Education and Her Majestyâs Treasury.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no McKinsey employees working directly on the Departmentâs Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has consulted with our key Partner Organisations during the Spending Review process and Her Majestyâs Treasury have undertaken a public consultation on the Spending Review which closed on 4<sup>th</sup> September.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9317","2015-09-10T16:39:47.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417130/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417130/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Mckinsey and Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many employees of McKinsey are working on his Department's spending review; for how long those employees have been so engaged; what remit those staff have been given; what the cost to the public purse is of such staff; and if he will list which organisations and individuals his Department has consulted during that spending review.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417131","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>There are four pieces of work where McKinsey have been providing assistance to the Department:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>operating costs across the Department and Partner Organisations;</li><li>the cost of goods and services procured from third parties, led by the Crown Commercial Service;</li><li>a review of the Student Loans Company; and</li><li>cost drivers in Further Education, jointly with the Department for Education and Her Majestyâs Treasury.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no McKinsey employees working directly on the Departmentâs Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has consulted with our key Partner Organisations during the Spending Review process and Her Majestyâs Treasury have undertaken a public consultation on the Spending Review which closed on 4<sup>th</sup> September.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9316","2015-09-10T16:39:47.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417131/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417131/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Mckinsey and Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what reviews his Department is conducting with assistance from McKinsey.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417132","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-05","<p>As of 8 September, 6,731 vouchers had been redeemed with total value over Â£11m.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-11-05T08:52:38.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417132/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417132/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Small Businesses: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 7500, how many vouchers were redeemed under the Growth Vouchers scheme.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417133","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>Borrowers from other EU countries who remain in the UK after completing their studies make repayments through the UK tax system in the usual way. The Student Loans Company (SLC) informs any borrower, regardless of nationality, going abroad of their obligations to repay and the methods of repayment available to them.</p><p> </p><p>If a borrower who has moved abroad fails to meet their obligations to repay, the SLC will undertake a variety of actions to recover payments. These include the use of international trace services and debt collection agencies.</p><p> </p><p>Collection across the EU is underpinned by EC regulation 44/2001, which allows the SLC to obtain judgments in UK Courts, which can be enforced by courts in other EU countries.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-15T15:57:59.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417133/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417133/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that students from other EU countries repay student loans taken out in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417134","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Government has commissioned Sir Paul Nurse to lead an independent review of the Research Councils. As part of the review, there was an open call for evidence which received over 250 responses. Sir Paul is supported by Advisory and Reference Groups representing a range of academic disciplines, universities, business and HE organisations as well as the Research Councils themselves.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-10T16:38:17.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417134/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417134/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Research Councils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he has received on the future of the Research Councils.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417135","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government identified â8 Great Technologiesâ in autumn 2012 to highlight key emerging technologies for the UK and increased investment by Â£600 million to accelerate their application and commercialisation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table provides a non-exclusive list of projects and programmes funded by BIS through Research Councils and InnovateUK relating to the â8 Great Technologiesâ from the time of publication to January 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We do not routinely keep records classifying all publically-funded projects and programmes since 2010 according to the 8 Great Technologies, and it would only be possible to provide this information at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Big Data:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Area</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>AHRC</p></td><td><p>Digital transformations in community research</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BBSRC</p></td><td><p>Bioinformatics and biological resources fund</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BBSRC</p></td><td><p>Big Data Infrastructure projects</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BBSRC</p></td><td><p>Institutes coordination grants</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BBSRC</p></td><td><p>Open Microscopy Environment (with Wellcome trust)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BBSRC</p></td><td><p>DNA Synthesis 2 capital investment</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>EPSRC</p></td><td><p>Capacity increase at Research Data Facility in Edinburgh</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ESRC</p></td><td><p>Administrative Data Research Network</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MRC</p></td><td><p>UK Health Informatics Research Institute</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MRC</p></td><td><p>Capability development to better understand health and disease</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MRC</p></td><td><p>Support to 100,000 Genomes project</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NERC</p></td